ember 19, 2019|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> [[Shout Factory|Shout Studios]] will distribute in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/shout-studios-misbehaviour-keira-knightley-gugu-mbatha-raw-1202884335/|title=Shout! Studios Lands Pageant Drama \u2018Misbehaviour\u2019 Starring Keira Knightley & Gugu Mbatha-Raw|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Due to the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]] the film will be released through [[video on demand]] in the United Kingdom on 15 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/04/keira-knightley-starrer-misbehaviour-uk-ireland-film-releases-heading-online-early-due-to-coronavirus-disruption-1202901336/|title=Keira Knightley Starrer \u2018Misbehaviour\u2019 \u2013 UK & Ireland Film Releases Heading Online Early Due To Coronavirus Disruption|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Tom|last=Grater|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n{{As of|2020|3|18|df=UK}}, ''Misbehaviour'' has grossed the equivalent of $426,765 in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"BOM\"/><ref name=\"NUM\"/>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 88% based on 25 reviews, with an average rating of 6.45/10. The site's critics consensus reads: \"''Misbehaviour''{{'}}s overall arc will be familiar to fans of feelgood British cinema \u2013 and so will the way it triumphs over formula to tell a thoroughly crowd-pleasing story.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/misbehaviour|title=Misbehaviour (2020)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|9148706}}\n\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Path\u00e9 films]]\n[[Category:BBC Films films]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox films]]\n[[Category:Beauty pageant films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1970s]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1970]]\n[[Category:British films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Miss World 1970]]\n", "name_user": "SchroCat", "label": "safe", "comment": "EngvarB, date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Misbehaviour_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Deconinck", "text_new": "'''Deconinck''' is a Dutch/Belgian surname that may refer to\n*[[Bernard Deconinck]] (1936\u20132020), French track cyclist\n*[[Jilke Deconinck]] (born 1995), Belgian association football player\n{{Surname}}\n\n{{Short pages monitor}}<!-- This long comment was added to the page to prevent it from being listed on Special:Shortpages. It and the accompanying monitoring template were generated via Template:Long comment. Please do not remove the monitor template without removing the comment as well.-->\n", "text_old": "'''Deconinck''' is a Dutch/Belgian surname that may refer to\n*[[Bernard Deconinck]] (born 1936), French track cyclist\n*[[Jilke Deconinck]] (born 1995), Belgian association football player\n{{Surname}}\n\n{{Short pages monitor}}<!-- This long comment was added to the page to prevent it from being listed on Special:Shortpages. It and the accompanying monitoring template were generated via Template:Long comment. Please do not remove the monitor template without removing the comment as well.-->\n", "name_user": "EricWR", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deconinck"}
{"title_page": "Eastern New Mexico University", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n|name = Eastern New Mexico University\n|image = Eastern New Mexico University seal.svg\n|image_size = 200\n|motto = Explore. Experience. Excel.<ref name=\"enmu.edu\">https://www.enmu.edu/about/general-information/enmu-facts-figures</ref>\n|established = 1927\n|type = [[Public university|Public]]\n|president = Dr. Jeff Elwell\n|city = [[Portales, New Mexico|Portales]]\n|state = [[New Mexico]]\n|country = United States\n|students =6,027 (Fall 2017)<ref>{{cite news | title=Eastern New Mexico University hits its highest enrollment | url=http://www.santafenewmexican.com/news/briefs/eastern-new-mexico-university-hits-its-highest-enrollment/article_4b0bd7a3-888b-51ec-8d68-3c47041a20da.html | accessdate=November 15, 2017 | work=Santa Fe New Mexican | agency=Associated Press | date=September 12, 2017}}</ref>\n|faculty = 161 full-time\n|campus = [[suburbs|suburban]]/small town, {{convert|433|acre|km2}} (main campus)<ref name=\"enmu.edu\">https://www.enmu.edu/about/general-information/enmu-facts-figures</ref>\n| athletics = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[NCAA Division II|Division&nbsp;II]] \u2013 [[Lone Star Conference|Lone Star]]\n|nickname = [[Eastern New Mexico Greyhounds|Greyhounds]]\n|colors = Green & Silver<ref>{{cite manual|url=https://my.enmu.edu/c/document_library/get_file?uuid=e68089af-5455-48c3-9ddb-4e3a3cf638ea&groupId=3872218 |title=ENMU Brand Identity Guide |accessdate=2017-04-11}}</ref><br/>{{color box|#006633}}&nbsp;{{color box|#A7A9AC}}\n|website = {{url|www.enmu.edu}}\n|logo = Eastern New Mexico University logo.svg\n|logo_size = 200\n}}\n\n'''Eastern New Mexico University''' ('''ENMU''' or '''Eastern''') is a [[public university]] with a main campus in [[Portales, New Mexico]], and two associate degree-granting branches, one at [[Ruidoso, New Mexico|Ruidoso]] and one at [[Roswell, New Mexico|Roswell]]. ENMU is New Mexico's largest regional comprehensive university and is the most recently founded state university in New Mexico (legislated in 1927, opened in 1934). It is a federally designated [[Hispanic-serving institution]] and a member of the [[Hispanic Association of Colleges and Universities]]. The ENMU System consists of three campuses.\n\n==History==\n[[File:ENMU Administration building from NW 1.JPG|thumb|left|Main administration building]]\n[[Image:ENMU1.jpg|thumb|A view of the main quad of ENMU.]]\n[[File:Walkway outside Golden Library, NMU.jpg|thumb|Central campus walkway]]\nThe New Mexico legislature approved the construction and staffing of a [[normal school]] in eastern [[New Mexico]] in 1927, and approved [[Appropriation (law)|appropriation]] for construction in 1929, but the [[Stock Market Crash of 1929]] and the [[Great Depression]] hindered the school's opening, which was delayed until 1934 (construction had begun in 1931).\n\nFrom 1934 to 1940, the institution, first named '''Eastern New Mexico Junior College (ENMJC)''' operated as a [[community college]].<ref>http://ftp.rootsweb.com/pub/usgenweb/nm/roosevelt/history/history.txt</ref> In 1940, the third and fourth years of college were first offered, leading to a [[bachelor's degree]], and the institution was renamed '''Eastern New Mexico College''' ('''ENMC'''). ENMC was accredited by the [[North Central Association of Colleges and Secondary Schools]] as a four-year [[liberal arts college]] in 1946\u201347. Graduate work leading to the [[master's degree]] in some departments was added in 1949, and on April 5, 1949, the Board of Regents approved the change of the institution's name to '''Eastern New Mexico University'''.\n\n==ENMU System==\nENMU's main campus (ENMU-Portales), consisting of over {{convert|400|acre|km2}},<ref name=\"enmu.edu\"/> is located in Portales on the extreme eastern border of New Mexico, in the [[Eastern New Mexico]]/[[Llano Estacado]] region about halfway between the northern and southern boundaries of the state. (Portales is {{convert|90|mi|km}} northeast of [[Roswell, New Mexico|Roswell]], {{convert|120|mi|km}} southwest of [[Amarillo, Texas]], and {{convert|110|mi|km}} northwest of [[Lubbock, Texas]].) ENMU owns [[KENW (TV)]] and [[KENW-FM]], a public television and radio station that are housed and operated on the main campus. The president of ENMU-Portales also serves as the chancellor for the ENMU System.\n\nThe '''ENMU Ruidoso Campus''', ENMU-Ruidoso, is a two-year college or community college (one of 18 in New Mexico) and an official branch of ENMU (branch status being granted in July 2005). Undergraduate and graduate coursework completed at the ENMU-Ruidoso campus is transferable for credit toward an undergraduate or graduate degree at ENMU-Portales, and, typically other undergraduate/graduate institutions in the United States. In 1991, the Ruidoso location had been established as the '''ENMU Ruidoso Branch Community College''' and offered two-year college academic and vocational programs. ENMU-Ruidoso offers Certificates of Completion, [[Associate of Science]], [[Associate of Arts]], and [[Associate of Applied Science]] degrees, as well as community education classes, customized training workshops, and adult basic education courses. It operates a One-Stop Career Center which provides free employment services for employers and job seekers in [[Lincoln County, New Mexico|Lincoln County]].  The center offers both an academic and vocational curriculum. (Ruidoso is located southwest of Portales, in a mountainous region of south-central New Mexico.)\n\nThe '''ENMU Roswell Campus''', ENMU-Roswell, also a two-year branch, offers a wide variety of programs. ENMU-Roswell was established in the fall of 1958. In the spring of 1967, the institution moved to 12 buildings on {{convert|241|acre|km2}} of the former [[Walker Air Force Base]]. Roswell is one of New Mexico's larger cities, located in the southeast section of the state.\n\nENMU also offers online degrees.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eastern New Mexico University Online Degrees|url=https://www.enmu.edu/academics/degrees-programs/online-programs|accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref> ENMU's online degrees in the fields of business and education are the most affordable in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 Most Affordable U.S. Online Colleges|url=http://www.onlineu.org/college-rankings/most-affordable|accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Academic organization==\nENMU-Portales consists of four colleges and a graduate school:\n\n;College of Business\n\n;College of Education and Technology\n*Department of Educational Studies\n*Department of Curriculum and Instruction\n*Department of Agriculture, Food Science and Kinesiology <ref>{{cite web|title=College of Education and Technology|url=https://www.enmu.edu/academics/colleges-departments/college-of-education-and-technology|accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n;College of Fine Arts\n*Department of Art\n*Department of Communication\n*Department of Music\n*Department of Theatre and Digital Filmmaking\n\n;College of Liberal Arts and Sciences\n*Department of Anthropology and Applied Archaeology\n*Department of Biology\n*Department of Health and Human Services (Communicative Disorders, Social Work, Nursing, Emergency Management)\n*Department of History, Social Sciences and Religion\n*Department of Languages and Literature\n*Department of Mathematical Sciences\n*Department of Physical Sciences (Chemistry, Physics, Aviation Science)\n*Department of Psychology and Political Science\n\n;Graduate School\n*Anthropology\n*Biology\n*Business Administration\n*Chemistry\n**Analytical Chemistry\n**Biochemistry\n**Organic Chemistry\n**Physical Chemistry\n*Communication\n*Communicative Disorders\n*Counseling\n*Education\n**Alternative Licensure\n***Elementary Education\n***Secondary Education\n***Special Education\n**Bilingual Education\n**Career and Technical Education\n**Early Childhood Education\n**Education Administration\n**Educational Technology\n**Gifted Education Pedagogy\n**Pedagogy and Learning\n**Reading/Literacy\n**School Counseling\n**Secondary Education\n**Special Education\n**Special Education Pedagogy\n*Physical Education\n**Coaching\n**Sport Administration\n*Nursing\n\n==Other facilities==\nAmong ENMU's other facilities are 5 museums, an art gallery, and a library.\n\n===Golden Student Success Center===\nThe Golden Student Success Center (GSSC) construction was completed in 2018 replacing the original Golden Library building. The building now houses the Golden Library, the Runnels Gallery and the offices of Tutoring and Supplemental Instruction and Distance Learning.<ref name=\"Golden Student Success Center GSSC\">{{cite web|title=Golden Student Success Center (GSSC)|url=https://www.enmu.edu/about/campus-facilities/campus-buildings/academic-general-facilities/golden-student-success-center|accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Golden Library\nThe Golden Library features General Collections, Special Collections and Government Information. Special Collections includes the Jack Williamson Science Fiction Library, Southwest Collection (including New Mexico collections), University archives, and local history. The General Collection includes newspapers, serials, juvenile books, and K-12 curriculum materials.<ref name=\"Golden Student Success Center GSSC\"/>\n\n;Jack Williamson Science Fiction Library\nThe [[Jack Williamson]] Science Fiction Library is part of the Special Collections and has one of the top science fiction collections in the world with over 30,000 volumes, including science fiction books, science fiction [[pulp magazine]]s dating back to the early 1900s, manuscripts, correspondence, and photographs.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.enmu.edu/academics/library/collections/jwsf.shtml |author= Bundy, Gene |title= Jack Williamson Science Fiction Library |publisher= ENMU |accessdate= August 31, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;Runnels Gallery\nThe Runnels Gallery is an exhibit space open to the public that features art by ENMU students, ENMU faculty, and guest artists. Runnels Gallery has hosted national juried exhibitions for artists working in various mediums including two-dimensional, three-dimensional and photography.\n\n===ENMU Museums===\n;Dr. Antonio Gennaro Natural History Museum \nThe Dr. Antonio Gennaro Natural History Museum is affiliated with the ENMU Department of Biology.<ref name=\"ENMU edu\">{{cite web|url= https://www.enmu.edu/about/general-information/local-events-and-info/arts-and-culture/natural-history-museum|title=The Dr. Antonio Gennaro Natural History Museum|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=|website=Eastern New Mexico University|publisher=ENMU |access-date=8 February 2018}}</ref> The purpose of the museum is to educate the public about the diversity of life while emphasizing the natural heritage of eastern New Mexico and the greater Southwest, particularly the Llano Estacado.<ref name=\"ENMU edu\"/> Formerly known as the Eastern New Mexico University Natural History Museum, the museum was renamed and dedicated to Dr. Gennaro in spring 2016.<ref name=\"ENMU edu\"/>  In addition to the taxidermy and study skins on display,<ref name=\"ENMU Natural History Museum\">{{cite web|url= https://nmsmallmuseumguide.com/tag/natural-history/|title=ENMU Natural History Museum|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=|website=New Mexico Small Museum Guide|publisher=NM Small Museum Guide|access-date=8 February 2018}}</ref> the museum features a live animal exhibit with both native and non-native species.<ref name=\"ENMU edu\"/> Gennaro came to ENMU in 1966 as an associate professor of biological sciences and went on to become a nationally recognized researcher. He started ENMU's vertebrate collection for the museum. He authored and published two books, ''Nature's Way'' and ''Wildlife Falsehoods''.\n\n;Blackwater Draw Museum\nThe original [[Blackwater Draw|Blackwater Draw Museum]] opened in 1969 at the midway point between Clovis and Portales to display artifacts uncovered at the Blackwater Locality No. 1 site and illustrate life at the Blackwater Draw site during the Clovis period (over 13,000 years ago) through the recent historic period. In 2017, the museum was moved to the ENMU campus and expanded to more broadly incorporate anthropology and related topics.\n\n;Miles Mineral Museum\nThe Miles [[Mineral]] Museum features a comprehensive collection of [[geological]] specimens representative of the [[Pecos River]] [[valley]] area, as well as a sampling of specimens from other regions, including several [[meteorites]].<ref name=\"Museum USA\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309160905/http://www.museumsusa.org/museums/info/7007|title=Miles Mineral museum|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=|website=www.museumsusa.org|publisher=Stories USA, Inc.|access-date=9 March 2018|quote=}}</ref> The bulk of the objects contained within the museum were once part of the private collection of amateur [[geologists]] and mineral enthusiasts, Mr. and Mrs. Fred Miles.<ref name=\"ENMU Natural History Museum\"/> [[ENMU]] purchased the [approximately] 2,500 piece<ref name=\"ENMU Natural History Museum\"/><ref name=\"Museum USA\"/> collection of [[geological]], [[archaeological]], and [[anthropological]] specimens from the couple in 1967.<ref name=\"Museum USA\"/> Many additional specimens have been added to the museum over the years since that time. The entire collection was originally displayed at a single ENMU facility named the Miles Museum, which opened in 1969.<ref name=\"Museum USA\"/>  In 1984 the objects in the collection were divided up into two categories, and two separate museums were formed to display them; the Miles Mineral Museum and the [[Eastern New Mexico University#Miles Anthropology Museum|Miles Anthropology Museum]].<ref name=\"Museum USA\"/>  The Miles Mineral Museum is now located in Roosevelt Hall, adjacent to the [[#Dr. Antonio Gennaro Natural History Museum|Dr. Antonio Gennaro Natural History museum]], on the ENMU campus.\n\nMr. Fred Miles and Mrs. Gladys Miles began collecting mineral and [[fossil]] specimens along the Pecos River after they moved to [[Roswell, New Mexico|Roswell]], [[New Mexico]], in 1928.<ref name=\"Clovis dept commerce\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309160905/http://www.museumsusa.org/museums/info/7007|title=Historical Attractions of Clovis|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=2018|website=www.clovisnm.org|publisher=Clovis Chamber of Commerce|access-date=9 March 2018|quote=}}</ref> They were prolific collectors for 40 years, scouring the Pecos River valley for specimens.<ref name=\"Clovis dept commerce\"/> They particularly enjoyed finding [[Native Americans in the United States|native American]] [[Artifact (archaeology)|artifacts]] and a specific type of [[quartz crystal]] formation referred to as [[Pecos Diamonds]].<ref name=\"Clovis dept commerce\"/> For several decades<ref name=\"ENMU Natural History Museum\"/> they displayed the majority of their enormous collection at a Texaco [[Filling station|service station]] in Roswell operated by Mr. Miles, who enjoyed showing it to inquisitive customers.<ref name=\"Clovis dept commerce\"/><ref name=\"Museum USA\"/>\n\n;Miles Anthropology Museum\nThe Miles Anthropology Museum is home to various anthropological and archeological specimens collected by amateur anthropologists Fred and Gladys Miles, as well as to other collections from digs in the region. The private collection of Mr. and Mrs. Miles was also used as the foundation of the [[Eastern New Mexico University#Miles Mineral Museum|Miles Mineral Museum]]. Both museums are located in Roosevelt Hall in a space that was once the first dining hall on the campus.\n\n==Athletics==\n{{main|Eastern New Mexico Greyhounds and Zias}}\n[[File:Athletics-Volleyball vs ENMU-8350 (15440320745).jpg|thumb|The Zias volleyball team in action against the [[Texas A&M\u2013Commerce Lions women's volleyball|Texas A&M\u2013Commerce Lions]] in 2014]]\nENMU's athletic teams participate in the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[NCAA Division II|Division&nbsp;II]] [[Lone Star Conference]]. The men's and women's teams are nicknamed the '''[[Greyhound]]s'''. Prior to 2015, the women's teams were nicknamed the '''[[Zia people (New Mexico)|Zias]]'''. In early 2015, students, faculty and staff voted to discontinue the Zia nickname and the women's teams become Greyhounds alongside the men's teams. ENMU vacated five seasons of wins in several sports starting from the 2008\u201309 season after the university self-reported over 100 eligibility violations.<ref>{{cite news | title=Eastern New Mexico on probation, to vacate five seasons of wins | url=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/story/_/id/13560995/eastern-new-mexico-university-probation-vacate-five-seasons-wins | accessdate=November 15, 2017 | work=ESPN | agency=Associated Press | date=September 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Greek life ==\nENMU currently features two active associated social [[fraternity|fraternities]] and two active associated social [[sorority|sororities]]. Historically, the school featured several additional social fraternities. The school also features several honors fraternities\n\n=== Social sororities ===\n* [[Chi Omega]] (active)\n* [[Zeta Tau Alpha]] (active)\n\n=== Social fraternities ===\n* [[Kappa Sigma]] (active)\n* [[Pi Kappa Alpha]] (?-suspended 1993)\n* [[Phi Kappa Psi]] (1969-dormant 2006)<ref name=\"phipsi\">{{Cite book | last =Phi Kappa Psi | first = | authorlink =Phi Kappa Psi | title = Grand Catalogue of the Phi Kappa Psi Fraternity | place = White Plains, NY | publisher = Bernard C. Harris Publishing Company | volume = | year = 1997 | edition = 14 | pages = | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = | oclc =324731269}}</ref>\n* [[Phi Mu Alpha Sinfonia]] (active)\n* [[Sigma Alpha Epsilon]] (1963-dormant 2000s)\n* [[Sigma Nu]] (1966-dormant 2001)\n* [[Sigma Chi]] (1967-suspended by ENMU in 2017)<ref name=\"enmnews\">{{cite web|url=https://www.easternnewmexiconews.com/story/2017/01/17/news/enmu-fraternity-suspended-for-two-years/150349.html|title=ENMU fraternity suspended for two years|last=staff|date=January 17, 2017|work=The Eastern New Mexico News|accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Honorary/Academic/Service organizations ===\n* [[Alpha Psi Omega]] (active)\n* [[Alpha Sigma Lambda]] (active)\n* [[Delta Mu Delta]] (active, established 1981)\n* [[Kappa Delta Pi]] (active)\n* [[Kappa Kappa Psi]] (active, chapter established 1949)\n* [[Phi Alpha (honor society)|Pi Alpha]] (active)\n* [[Psi Chi]] (active)\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n=== Art ===\n* [[Michael Kanteena]]\n* [[Daryush Shokof]]\n* [[Derek \"Mason\" Warner]]\n* [[Paul Harold O'Dell]]\n\n=== Athletics ===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Dana Altman]]\n* [[Mike Boit]]\n* [[Don Carthel]]\n* [[Benjy Dial]]\n* [[Gerald Dockery]]\n* [[Mark Fox (basketball coach)|Mark Fox]]\n* [[Conrad Hamilton]]\n* [[Derrick Harden]]\n* [[Larry Harris (basketball)|Larry Harris]]\n* [[Larry Hays]]\n* [[Greg Hyder]]\n* [[Pete Jaquess]]\n* [[Steve Kragthorpe]]\n* [[Matt Simon (American football)|Matt Simon]]\n* [[Michael Sinclair (American football)|Mike Sinclair]]\n* [[Bill Snyder]]\n* [[Steve Spray]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== Film and television ===\n* [[Ronny Cox]]\n* [[Steven Michael Quezada]]\n* [[Daryush Shokof]]\n\n=== Government ===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Juan Babauta]]\n* [[Mickey D. Barnett]]\n* [[Robert C. Brack]]\n* [[Matthew Chandler (District Attorney)|Matthew Chandler]]\n* [[Edward L. Chavez]]\n* [[Sharon Clahchischilliage]]\n* [[Anna Crook]]\n* [[Candy Ezzell]]\n* [[Ed Foreman]]\n* [[Miguel Garcia (politician)|Miguel Garcia]]\n* [[Carroll Leavell]]\n* [[James Madalena]]\n* [[Katherine D. Ortega]]\n* [[Steve Pearce (politician)|Stevan Pearce]]\n* [[Dennis Roch]]\n* [[Clemente Sanchez (politician)|Clemente Sanchez]]\n* [[Louis E. Saavedra]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== Law ===\n* [[John E. Douglas]]\n* [[Arthur M. Dula]]\n\n=== Literature and publishing ===\n* [[Michael Blake (author)|Michael Blake]]\n* [[Diana Ossana]]\n* [[Jack Williamson]]\n\n=== Science ===\n* [[Clyde Snow]]\n\n== Notable faculty ==\n* [[Jeffrion L. Aubry]]\n* [[Bobby Ray Baldock]]\n* [[Harold Elliott]]\n* [[Jeffery Elwell]] \n* [[Paul Krutak]]\n* [[Greg Lyne]]\n* [[Jack Scott (American football)|Jack Scott]]\n* [[Christopher Stasheff]]\n* Jack Williamson\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Eastern New Mexico University}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://www.goeasternathletics.com ENMU Athletics website]\n\n{{Lone Star Conference navbox}}\n{{Colleges and universities in New Mexico}}\n\n{{Coord|34|10|37|N|103|20|55|W|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Eastern New Mexico University| ]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1934]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Roosevelt County, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Education in Roosevelt County, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Education in Lincoln County, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Education in Chaves County, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:1934 establishments in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Portales, New Mexico]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n|name = Eastern New Mexico University\n|image = Eastern New Mexico University seal.svg\n|image_size = 200\n|motto = Explore. Experience. Excel.<ref name=\"enmu.edu\">https://www.enmu.edu/about/general-information/enmu-facts-figures</ref>\n|established = 1927\n|type = [[Public university|Public]]\n|president = Dr. Jeff Elwell\n|city = [[Portales, New Mexico|Portales]]\n|state = [[New Mexico]]\n|country = United States\n|students =6,027 (Fall 2017)<ref>{{cite news | title=Eastern New Mexico University hits its highest enrollment | url=http://www.santafenewmexican.com/news/briefs/eastern-new-mexico-university-hits-its-highest-enrollment/article_4b0bd7a3-888b-51ec-8d68-3c47041a20da.html | accessdate=November 15, 2017 | work=Santa Fe New Mexican | agency=Associated Press | date=September 12, 2017}}</ref>\n|faculty = 161 full-time\n|campus = [[suburbs|suburban]]/small town, {{convert|433|acre|km2}} (main campus)<ref name=\"enmu.edu\">https://www.enmu.edu/about/general-information/enmu-facts-figures</ref>\n| athletics = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[NCAA Division II|Division&nbsp;II]] \u2013 [[Lone Star Conference|Lone Star]]\n|nickname = [[Eastern New Mexico Greyhounds|Greyhounds]]\n|colors = Green & Silver<ref>{{cite manual|url=https://my.enmu.edu/c/document_library/get_file?uuid=e68089af-5455-48c3-9ddb-4e3a3cf638ea&groupId=3872218 |title=ENMU Brand Identity Guide |accessdate=2017-04-11}}</ref><br/>{{color box|#006633}}&nbsp;{{color box|#A7A9AC}}\n|website = {{url|www.enmu.edu}}\n|logo = Eastern New Mexico University logo.svg\n|logo_size = 200\n}}\n\n'''Eastern New Mexico University''' ('''ENMU''' or '''Eastern''') is a [[public university]] with a main campus in [[Portales, New Mexico]]. ENMU is New Mexico's largest regional comprehensive university and is the most recently founded state university in New Mexico (legislated in 1927, opened in 1934). It is a federally designated [[Hispanic-serving institution]] and a member of the [[Hispanic Association of Colleges and Universities]]. The ENMU System consists of three campuses. ENMU's main campus (ENMU-Portales) is located in Portales; there are two associate degree-granting branches, one at [[Ruidoso, New Mexico|Ruidoso]] and one at [[Roswell, New Mexico|Roswell]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:ENMU Administration building from NW 1.JPG|thumb|left|Main administration building]]\n[[Image:ENMU1.jpg|thumb|A view of the main quad of ENMU.]]\n[[File:Walkway outside Golden Library, NMU.jpg|thumb|Central campus walkway]]\nThe New Mexico legislature approved the construction and staffing of a [[normal school]] in eastern [[New Mexico]] in 1927, and approved [[Appropriation (law)|appropriation]] for construction in 1929, but the [[Stock Market Crash of 1929]] and the [[Great Depression]] hindered the school's opening, which was delayed until 1934 (construction had begun in 1931).\n\nFrom 1934 to 1940, the institution, first named '''Eastern New Mexico Junior College (ENMJC)''' operated as a [[community college]].<ref>http://ftp.rootsweb.com/pub/usgenweb/nm/roosevelt/history/history.txt</ref> In 1940, the third and fourth years of college were first offered, leading to a [[bachelor's degree]], and the institution was renamed '''Eastern New Mexico College''' ('''ENMC'''). ENMC was accredited by the [[North Central Association of Colleges and Secondary Schools]] as a four-year [[liberal arts college]] in 1946\u201347. Graduate work leading to the [[master's degree]] in some departments was added in 1949, and on April 5, 1949, the Board of Regents approved the change of the institution's name to '''Eastern New Mexico University'''.\n\n==ENMU System==\nENMU's main campus (ENMU-Portales), consisting of over {{convert|400|acre|km2}},<ref name=\"enmu.edu\"/> is located in Portales on the extreme eastern border of New Mexico, in the [[Eastern New Mexico]]/[[Llano Estacado]] region about halfway between the northern and southern boundaries of the state. (Portales is {{convert|90|mi|km}} northeast of [[Roswell, New Mexico|Roswell]], {{convert|120|mi|km}} southwest of [[Amarillo, Texas]], and {{convert|110|mi|km}} northwest of [[Lubbock, Texas]].) ENMU owns [[KENW (TV)]] and [[KENW-FM]], a public television and radio station that are housed and operated on the main campus. The president of ENMU-Portales also serves as the chancellor for the ENMU System.\n\nThe '''ENMU Ruidoso Campus''', ENMU-Ruidoso, is a two-year college or community college (one of 18 in New Mexico) and an official branch of ENMU (branch status being granted in July 2005). Undergraduate and graduate coursework completed at the ENMU-Ruidoso campus is transferable for credit toward an undergraduate or graduate degree at ENMU-Portales, and, typically other undergraduate/graduate institutions in the United States. In 1991, the Ruidoso location had been established as the '''ENMU Ruidoso Branch Community College''' and offered two-year college academic and vocational programs. ENMU-Ruidoso offers Certificates of Completion, [[Associate of Science]], [[Associate of Arts]], and [[Associate of Applied Science]] degrees, as well as community education classes, customized training workshops, and adult basic education courses. It operates a One-Stop Career Center which provides free employment services for employers and job seekers in [[Lincoln County, New Mexico|Lincoln County]].  The center offers both an academic and vocational curriculum. (Ruidoso is located southwest of Portales, in a mountainous region of south-central New Mexico.)\n\nThe '''ENMU Roswell Campus''', ENMU-Roswell, also a two-year branch, offers a wide variety of programs. ENMU-Roswell was established in the fall of 1958. In the spring of 1967, the institution moved to 12 buildings on {{convert|241|acre|km2}} of the former [[Walker Air Force Base]]. Roswell is one of New Mexico's larger cities, located in the southeast section of the state.\n\nENMU also offers online degrees.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eastern New Mexico University Online Degrees|url=https://www.enmu.edu/academics/degrees-programs/online-programs|accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref> ENMU's online degrees in the fields of business and education are the most affordable in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 Most Affordable U.S. Online Colleges|url=http://www.onlineu.org/college-rankings/most-affordable|accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Academic organization==\nENMU-Portales consists of four colleges and a graduate school:\n\n;College of Business\n\n;College of Education and Technology\n*Department of Educational Studies\n*Department of Curriculum and Instruction\n*Department of Agriculture, Food Science and Kinesiology <ref>{{cite web|title=College of Education and Technology|url=https://www.enmu.edu/academics/colleges-departments/college-of-education-and-technology|accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n;College of Fine Arts\n*Department of Art\n*Department of Communication\n*Department of Music\n*Department of Theatre and Digital Filmmaking\n\n;College of Liberal Arts and Sciences\n*Department of Anthropology and Applied Archaeology\n*Department of Biology\n*Department of Health and Human Services (Communicative Disorders, Social Work, Nursing, Emergency Management)\n*Department of History, Social Sciences and Religion\n*Department of Languages and Literature\n*Department of Mathematical Sciences\n*Department of Physical Sciences (Chemistry, Physics, Aviation Science)\n*Department of Psychology and Political Science\n\n;Graduate School\n*Anthropology\n*Biology\n*Business Administration\n*Chemistry\n**Analytical Chemistry\n**Biochemistry\n**Organic Chemistry\n**Physical Chemistry\n*Communication\n*Communicative Disorders\n*Counseling\n*Education\n**Alternative Licensure\n***Elementary Education\n***Secondary Education\n***Special Education\n**Bilingual Education\n**Career and Technical Education\n**Early Childhood Education\n**Education Administration\n**Educational Technology\n**Gifted Education Pedagogy\n**Pedagogy and Learning\n**Reading/Literacy\n**School Counseling\n**Secondary Education\n**Special Education\n**Special Education Pedagogy\n*Physical Education\n**Coaching\n**Sport Administration\n*Nursing\n\n==Other facilities==\nAmong ENMU's other facilities are 5 museums, an art gallery, and a library.\n\n===Golden Student Success Center===\nThe Golden Student Success Center (GSSC) construction was completed in 2018 replacing the original Golden Library building. The building now houses the Golden Library, the Runnels Gallery and the offices of Tutoring and Supplemental Instruction and Distance Learning.<ref name=\"Golden Student Success Center GSSC\">{{cite web|title=Golden Student Success Center (GSSC)|url=https://www.enmu.edu/about/campus-facilities/campus-buildings/academic-general-facilities/golden-student-success-center|accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Golden Library\nThe Golden Library features General Collections, Special Collections and Government Information. Special Collections includes the Jack Williamson Science Fiction Library, Southwest Collection (including New Mexico collections), University archives, and local history. The General Collection includes newspapers, serials, juvenile books, and K-12 curriculum materials.<ref name=\"Golden Student Success Center GSSC\"/>\n\n;Jack Williamson Science Fiction Library\nThe [[Jack Williamson]] Science Fiction Library is part of the Special Collections and has one of the top science fiction collections in the world with over 30,000 volumes, including science fiction books, science fiction [[pulp magazine]]s dating back to the early 1900s, manuscripts, correspondence, and photographs.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.enmu.edu/academics/library/collections/jwsf.shtml |author= Bundy, Gene |title= Jack Williamson Science Fiction Library |publisher= ENMU |accessdate= August 31, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;Runnels Gallery\nThe Runnels Gallery is an exhibit space open to the public that features art by ENMU students, ENMU faculty, and guest artists. Runnels Gallery has hosted national juried exhibitions for artists working in various mediums including two-dimensional, three-dimensional and photography.\n\n===ENMU Museums===\n;Dr. Antonio Gennaro Natural History Museum \nThe Dr. Antonio Gennaro Natural History Museum is affiliated with the ENMU Department of Biology.<ref name=\"ENMU edu\">{{cite web|url= https://www.enmu.edu/about/general-information/local-events-and-info/arts-and-culture/natural-history-museum|title=The Dr. Antonio Gennaro Natural History Museum|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=|website=Eastern New Mexico University|publisher=ENMU |access-date=8 February 2018}}</ref> The purpose of the museum is to educate the public about the diversity of life while emphasizing the natural heritage of eastern New Mexico and the greater Southwest, particularly the Llano Estacado.<ref name=\"ENMU edu\"/> Formerly known as the Eastern New Mexico University Natural History Museum, the museum was renamed and dedicated to Dr. Gennaro in spring 2016.<ref name=\"ENMU edu\"/>  In addition to the taxidermy and study skins on display,<ref name=\"ENMU Natural History Museum\">{{cite web|url= https://nmsmallmuseumguide.com/tag/natural-history/|title=ENMU Natural History Museum|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=|website=New Mexico Small Museum Guide|publisher=NM Small Museum Guide|access-date=8 February 2018}}</ref> the museum features a live animal exhibit with both native and non-native species.<ref name=\"ENMU edu\"/> Gennaro came to ENMU in 1966 as an associate professor of biological sciences and went on to become a nationally recognized researcher. He started ENMU's vertebrate collection for the museum. He authored and published two books, ''Nature's Way'' and ''Wildlife Falsehoods''.\n\n;Blackwater Draw Museum\nThe original [[Blackwater Draw|Blackwater Draw Museum]] opened in 1969 at the midway point between Clovis and Portales to display artifacts uncovered at the Blackwater Locality No. 1 site and illustrate life at the Blackwater Draw site during the Clovis period (over 13,000 years ago) through the recent historic period. In 2017, the museum was moved to the ENMU campus and expanded to more broadly incorporate anthropology and related topics.\n\n;Miles Mineral Museum\nThe Miles [[Mineral]] Museum features a comprehensive collection of [[geological]] specimens representative of the [[Pecos River]] [[valley]] area, as well as a sampling of specimens from other regions, including several [[meteorites]].<ref name=\"Museum USA\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309160905/http://www.museumsusa.org/museums/info/7007|title=Miles Mineral museum|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=|website=www.museumsusa.org|publisher=Stories USA, Inc.|access-date=9 March 2018|quote=}}</ref> The bulk of the objects contained within the museum were once part of the private collection of amateur [[geologists]] and mineral enthusiasts, Mr. and Mrs. Fred Miles.<ref name=\"ENMU Natural History Museum\"/> [[ENMU]] purchased the [approximately] 2,500 piece<ref name=\"ENMU Natural History Museum\"/><ref name=\"Museum USA\"/> collection of [[geological]], [[archaeological]], and [[anthropological]] specimens from the couple in 1967.<ref name=\"Museum USA\"/> Many additional specimens have been added to the museum over the years since that time. The entire collection was originally displayed at a single ENMU facility named the Miles Museum, which opened in 1969.<ref name=\"Museum USA\"/>  In 1984 the objects in the collection were divided up into two categories, and two separate museums were formed to display them; the Miles Mineral Museum and the [[Eastern New Mexico University#Miles Anthropology Museum|Miles Anthropology Museum]].<ref name=\"Museum USA\"/>  The Miles Mineral Museum is now located in Roosevelt Hall, adjacent to the [[#Dr. Antonio Gennaro Natural History Museum|Dr. Antonio Gennaro Natural History museum]], on the ENMU campus.\n\nMr. Fred Miles and Mrs. Gladys Miles began collecting mineral and [[fossil]] specimens along the Pecos River after they moved to [[Roswell, New Mexico|Roswell]], [[New Mexico]], in 1928.<ref name=\"Clovis dept commerce\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309160905/http://www.museumsusa.org/museums/info/7007|title=Historical Attractions of Clovis|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=2018|website=www.clovisnm.org|publisher=Clovis Chamber of Commerce|access-date=9 March 2018|quote=}}</ref> They were prolific collectors for 40 years, scouring the Pecos River valley for specimens.<ref name=\"Clovis dept commerce\"/> They particularly enjoyed finding [[Native Americans in the United States|native American]] [[Artifact (archaeology)|artifacts]] and a specific type of [[quartz crystal]] formation referred to as [[Pecos Diamonds]].<ref name=\"Clovis dept commerce\"/> For several decades<ref name=\"ENMU Natural History Museum\"/> they displayed the majority of their enormous collection at a Texaco [[Filling station|service station]] in Roswell operated by Mr. Miles, who enjoyed showing it to inquisitive customers.<ref name=\"Clovis dept commerce\"/><ref name=\"Museum USA\"/>\n\n;Miles Anthropology Museum\nThe Miles Anthropology Museum is home to various anthropological and archeological specimens collected by amateur anthropologists Fred and Gladys Miles, as well as to other collections from digs in the region. The private collection of Mr. and Mrs. Miles was also used as the foundation of the [[Eastern New Mexico University#Miles Mineral Museum|Miles Mineral Museum]]. Both museums are located in Roosevelt Hall in a space that was once the first dining hall on the campus.\n\n==Athletics==\n{{main|Eastern New Mexico Greyhounds and Zias}}\n[[File:Athletics-Volleyball vs ENMU-8350 (15440320745).jpg|thumb|The Zias volleyball team in action against the [[Texas A&M\u2013Commerce Lions women's volleyball|Texas A&M\u2013Commerce Lions]] in 2014]]\nENMU's athletic teams participate in the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[NCAA Division II|Division&nbsp;II]] [[Lone Star Conference]]. The men's and women's teams are nicknamed the '''[[Greyhound]]s'''. Prior to 2015, the women's teams were nicknamed the '''[[Zia people (New Mexico)|Zias]]'''. In early 2015, students, faculty and staff voted to discontinue the Zia nickname and the women's teams become Greyhounds alongside the men's teams. ENMU vacated five seasons of wins in several sports starting from the 2008\u201309 season after the university self-reported over 100 eligibility violations.<ref>{{cite news | title=Eastern New Mexico on probation, to vacate five seasons of wins | url=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/story/_/id/13560995/eastern-new-mexico-university-probation-vacate-five-seasons-wins | accessdate=November 15, 2017 | work=ESPN | agency=Associated Press | date=September 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Greek life ==\nENMU currently features two active associated social [[fraternity|fraternities]] and two active associated social [[sorority|sororities]]. Historically, the school featured several additional social fraternities. The school also features several honors fraternities\n\n=== Social sororities ===\n* [[Chi Omega]] (active)\n* [[Zeta Tau Alpha]] (active)\n\n=== Social fraternities ===\n* [[Kappa Sigma]] (active)\n* [[Pi Kappa Alpha]] (?-suspended 1993)\n* [[Phi Kappa Psi]] (1969-dormant 2006)<ref name=\"phipsi\">{{Cite book | last =Phi Kappa Psi | first = | authorlink =Phi Kappa Psi | title = Grand Catalogue of the Phi Kappa Psi Fraternity | place = White Plains, NY | publisher = Bernard C. Harris Publishing Company | volume = | year = 1997 | edition = 14 | pages = | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = | oclc =324731269}}</ref>\n* [[Phi Mu Alpha Sinfonia]] (active)\n* [[Sigma Alpha Epsilon]] (1963-dormant 2000s)\n* [[Sigma Nu]] (1966-dormant 2001)\n* [[Sigma Chi]] (1967-suspended by ENMU in 2017)<ref name=\"enmnews\">{{cite web|url=https://www.easternnewmexiconews.com/story/2017/01/17/news/enmu-fraternity-suspended-for-two-years/150349.html|title=ENMU fraternity suspended for two years|last=staff|date=January 17, 2017|work=The Eastern New Mexico News|accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Honorary/Academic/Service organizations ===\n* [[Alpha Psi Omega]] (active)\n* [[Alpha Sigma Lambda]] (active)\n* [[Delta Mu Delta]] (active, established 1981)\n* [[Kappa Delta Pi]] (active)\n* [[Kappa Kappa Psi]] (active, chapter established 1949)\n* [[Phi Alpha (honor society)|Pi Alpha]] (active)\n* [[Psi Chi]] (active)\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n=== Art ===\n* [[Michael Kanteena]]\n* [[Daryush Shokof]]\n* [[Derek \"Mason\" Warner]]\n* [[Paul Harold O'Dell]]\n\n=== Athletics ===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Dana Altman]]\n* [[Mike Boit]]\n* [[Don Carthel]]\n* [[Benjy Dial]]\n* [[Gerald Dockery]]\n* [[Mark Fox (basketball coach)|Mark Fox]]\n* [[Conrad Hamilton]]\n* [[Derrick Harden]]\n* [[Larry Harris (basketball)|Larry Harris]]\n* [[Larry Hays]]\n* [[Greg Hyder]]\n* [[Pete Jaquess]]\n* [[Steve Kragthorpe]]\n* [[Matt Simon (American football)|Matt Simon]]\n* [[Michael Sinclair (American football)|Mike Sinclair]]\n* [[Bill Snyder]]\n* [[Steve Spray]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== Film and television ===\n* [[Ronny Cox]]\n* [[Steven Michael Quezada]]\n* [[Daryush Shokof]]\n\n=== Government ===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Juan Babauta]]\n* [[Mickey D. Barnett]]\n* [[Robert C. Brack]]\n* [[Matthew Chandler (District Attorney)|Matthew Chandler]]\n* [[Edward L. Chavez]]\n* [[Sharon Clahchischilliage]]\n* [[Anna Crook]]\n* [[Candy Ezzell]]\n* [[Ed Foreman]]\n* [[Miguel Garcia (politician)|Miguel Garcia]]\n* [[Carroll Leavell]]\n* [[James Madalena]]\n* [[Katherine D. Ortega]]\n* [[Steve Pearce (politician)|Stevan Pearce]]\n* [[Dennis Roch]]\n* [[Clemente Sanchez (politician)|Clemente Sanchez]]\n* [[Louis E. Saavedra]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== Law ===\n* [[John E. Douglas]]\n* [[Arthur M. Dula]]\n\n=== Literature and publishing ===\n* [[Michael Blake (author)|Michael Blake]]\n* [[Diana Ossana]]\n* [[Jack Williamson]]\n\n=== Science ===\n* [[Clyde Snow]]\n\n== Notable faculty ==\n* [[Jeffrion L. Aubry]]\n* [[Bobby Ray Baldock]]\n* [[Harold Elliott]]\n* [[Jeffery Elwell]] \n* [[Paul Krutak]]\n* [[Greg Lyne]]\n* [[Jack Scott (American football)|Jack Scott]]\n* [[Christopher Stasheff]]\n* Jack Williamson\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Eastern New Mexico University}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://www.goeasternathletics.com ENMU Athletics website]\n\n{{Lone Star Conference navbox}}\n{{Colleges and universities in New Mexico}}\n\n{{Coord|34|10|37|N|103|20|55|W|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Eastern New Mexico University| ]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1934]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Roosevelt County, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Education in Roosevelt County, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Education in Lincoln County, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Education in Chaves County, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:1934 establishments in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Portales, New Mexico]]\n", "name_user": "ElKevbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eastern_New_Mexico_University"}
{"title_page": "William J. Breed", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name                    = William J. Breed\n| image                   = \n| image_size              = \n| caption                 = \n| birth_date              = {{birth date|1928|8|3|mf=y}}\n| birth_place             = [[Massillon, Ohio]]\n| death_date              = {{death date and age|2013|1|22|1928|8|03|df=y}}\n| death_place             = [[Flagstaff, Arizona]]\n| residence               = \n| citizenship             =\n| nationality             = \n| ethnicity               =\n| field                   = [[Geomorphology]]<br>[[Geology]]<br>[[Vertebrate]][[Paleontology]]\n| work_institution        = [[U.S. Geological Survey]]<br>[[Museum of Northern Arizona]]<br>Nature Expeditions International\n| alma_mater              = [[Massillon Washington High School]]<br>[[Denison University]]<br>[[University of Arizona]]\n| doctoral_advisor        = \n| doctoral_students       = \n| known_for               = [[Grand Canyon]]<br>[[Northern Arizona]]<br>[[Dilophosaurus]]<br>[[Lystrosaurus]]\n| author_abbreviation_bot = \n| author_abbreviation_zoo = \n| prizes                  = [[Fulbright Scholarship]] (1957-58)<br>[[National Science Foundation]] - Antarctic Service Medal (1977)<br>Gladys Cole Award - [[Geological Society of America]](1982)\n| religion                = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''William J. \"Bill\" Breed''' (August 3, 1928 - January 22, 2013) was an American [[geologist]], [[paleontologist]], naturalist and author in Northern [[Arizona]]. He was a renowned expert on the geology of the [[Grand Canyon]].<ref name=\"azdailysun\">[http://azdailysun.com/news/local/obituaries/william-breed-renowned-mna-geologist-dies-in-flagstaff/article_41857e06-1387-53d0-bf6f-f3c469222f65.html ''Arizona Daily Sun'', January 24, 2013, A2]</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nWilliam J. Breed was born August 3, 1928 in [[Massillon, Ohio]], son of Grace Amelia (n\u00e9e Snyder) and Earl Fremont Breed. After graduating from [[Massillon Washington High School]], he served in the U.S. Army Corps of Military Police in South Korea and Japan (1946\u201348).  He received his [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] from [[Denison University]], then his [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] and [[Master of Science|M.S.]] from [[University of Arizona]], finishing in 1960.  He married Carol S. Breed daughter of [[James Neilson (director)]] and Mrs. Ruth Swope (n\u00e9e Rogers) in 1965. The couple had one daughter, Amelia, who joined the family of four girls (Linda, Laura, Grace, Pamela) from Carol's first marriage.<ref>''Arizona Daily Sun'', Dec. 18, 1965</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\nBill Breed was a [[Fulbright Scholar]] at [[Canterbury University]] in [[Christchurch]], New Zealand to study [[geomorphology]] in 1957-58.<ref name=\"CantonRepository\">''Canton Repository'', March 12, 1957</ref>\n\nBill Breed was a prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of [[Edwin D. McKee]].  Breed was Curator of Geology (1960\u201378), Head, Geology Department (1978\u201381) at the [[Museum of Northern Arizona]] in [[Flagstaff, Arizona]]. In 1969, Breed and [[Edwin H. Colbert]] were two of the four vertebrate paleontologists in Antarctica who helped solidify the acceptance of [[continental drift]] theory, by finding a 220-million-year-old fossil of a ''[[Lystrosaurus]]''.  In the 1970s, Breed completed numerous publications on the [[Grand Canyon]], including a geologic cross section map of the Grand Canyon, San Francisco Peaks and Verde Valley; and the book, ''Geology of the Grand Canyon''.<ref>[http://azdailysun.com/news/local/obituaries/william-breed-renowned-mna-geologist-dies-in-flagstaff/article_41857e06-1387-53d0-bf6f-f3c469222f65.html Arizona Daily Sun, January 24, 2013, A2;]</ref>\n\nA species of ''[[Dilophosaurus]], (D. breedorum)'', discovered by Sam Welles in Arizona in 1964 was named after William J. Breed and his wife at the time Carol S. Breed.<ref>Welles, S. P. (1984). \"Dilophosaurus wetherilli (Dinosauria, Theropoda), osteology and comparisons\". Palaeontogr. Abt. A 185: 85\u2013180.</ref> This name came out in a private publication distributed by Pickering,<ref>Olshevsky, George (1999-12-05). \"Dinosaur Genera List corrections #126\". Dinosaur Mailing List Archives. Cleveland Museum of Natural History. Retrieved 2008-06-25.</ref> but has not been accepted in other reviews of the genus.<ref>Gay, Robert (2001). \"New specimens of Dilophosaurus wetherilli (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the early Jurassic Kayenta Formation of northern Arizona\". Western Association of Vertebrate Paleontologists annual meeting volume Mesa, Arizona 1: 1.</ref><ref>Tykoski, R. S. & Rowe, T. (2004). \"Ceratosauria\". In: Weishampel, D.B., Dodson, P., & Osmolska, H. (Eds.) ''The Dinosauria'' (2nd edition). Berkeley: University of California Press. Pp. 47\u201370 {{ISBN|0-520-24209-2}}</ref><ref>[[Dilophosaurus]]</ref>\n\nAfter leaving the [[Museum of Northern Arizona]] in 1981, Breed became a naturalist guide for Nature Expeditions International and Betchart Expeditions leading trips to Alaska, New Zealand, [[Galapagos]], [[Namibia]], and Australia.  He became Curator Emeritus of the Museum of Northern Arizona in 2004.  In January 2013, shortly before his death, Breed was named a Distinguished Fellow of the Museum of Northern Arizona.<ref name=\"azdailysun\" />\n\nBreed was an active environmentalist with [[Ted Danson]] <ref>[http://newsweek.com/2011/03/20/my-favorite-mistake.html \"My Favorite Mistake\"] ''Newsweek''</ref> and many others.\n\n== Awards ==\n\n[[Fellow]] of the [[Geological Society of America]], the A.A.A.S, the Arizona Academy of Science, and the [[Museum of Northern Arizona]].<ref name=\"Museumof\">Museum of Northern Arizona Archive</ref><br>\n[[National Science Foundation]] - Antarctic Service Medal (1977)<ref name=\"Museumof\" /><br>\n[[Geological Society of America]] - Gladys Cole Award (1982)<ref name=\"Museumof\" /><br>\nDistinguished Citizen Award from [[Massillon Washington High School]] in 2005.<ref name=\"Museumof\" />\n\n== Publications ==\n\nBreed wrote or contributed to more than 80 scientific publications and popular magazines.<ref name=\"Museumof\" />\n*1964: \"Metacoceras bowmani, a new species of Nautiloid from the Toroweap Formation (Permian) of Arizona,\" ''[[Journal of Paleontology]]''; v.38, No.5, pp 877\u2013880 (with Halsey W. Miller Jr)\n*1965: \"An exotic occurrence of fresh water drum fish,\" ''[[Plateau (journal)|Plateau]]'' v. 37, No.3, p.&nbsp;5.\n*1967: \"Evolution of the Colorado River in Arizona\" 'Museum of Northern Arizona Bulletin' #44, pp 67 (with [[Edwin D. McKee]], R.F. Wilson, and Carol S. Breed.)\n*1969: \"A Pliocene river channel near Doney Crater, Arizona\" ''Journal of Arizona Academy of Sciences'', vol. 5, No.3, pp.&nbsp;177\u2013181.\n*1969: \"The Chuar Group of the Grand Canyon, Arizona.\" ''Geological Society of America Rocky Mountain Section, Abstracts with Programs,'' May 7\u201311, 1969, pp.&nbsp;23\u201324. (with [[Trevor D. Ford]])\n*1970: \"Hopi Pahos at the South Pole\" ''Plateau'' V. 42, No. 4, pp.&nbsp;125\n*1970: \"Triassic Tetrapods from Antarctica: Evidence of Continental Drift\" ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]'' V. 169, No. 3951, pp.&nbsp;1197\u20131201 (with David H Elliot, [[Edwin H. Colbert]], James Jensen and Jon S. Powell)\n*1971: \"Last Chance for Rainbow Bridge?\" ''Outdoor Arizona'', pp.&nbsp;38\u201341\n*1974: ''Geology of the Grand Canyon'', by William J. Breed and Evelyn C. Roat \n*1974: \"Red Mountain, Erosion or Explosion,\" ''Plateau'', Vol. 46, No. 3, pp.&nbsp;120\u2013122.\n*1975: ''Geologic Cross Section of the Grand Canyon - San Francisco Peaks - Verde Valley Region'' Zion Natural History Association, Springdale, Utah\n*1976: \"Our \"Unchanging\" Grand Canyon\", ''[[Arizona Highways]]'', Vol. 52, No. 5, p.&nbsp;12-15.\n*1977: \"Chitinozoans from the Late Precambrian Chuar Group of the Grand Canyon, Arizona\" ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]'', Vol. 195, No. 4279, pp.&nbsp;676\u2013679 (with Bonnie Bloeser, Wiliam J. Schopf and Robert J. Horodyski)\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links and references ==\n\n* ''Arizona Daily Sun'', January 24, 2013, A2 http://azdailysun.com/news/local/obituaries/william-breed-renowned-mna-geologist-dies-in-flagstaff/article_41857e06-1387-53d0-bf6f-f3c469222f65.html\n*''Newsweek'': [http://newsweek.com/2011/03/20/my-favorite-mistake.html My Favorite Mistake]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n<!-- This will add a notice to the bottom of the page and won't blank it! The new template which says that your draft is waiting for a review will appear at the bottom; simply ignore the old (grey) drafted templates and the old (red) decline templates. A bot will update your article submission. Until then, please don't change anything in this text box.  Just press \"Save page\". -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Breed, William J.}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:Denison University alumni]]\n[[Category:American paleontologists]]\n[[Category:American geologists]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Massillon, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Writers from Tucson, Arizona]]\n[[Category:People from Flagstaff, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Fulbright Scholars]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Geological Society of America]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name                    = William J. Breed\n| image                   = \n| image_size              = \n| caption                 = \n| birth_date              = {{birth date|1928|8|3|mf=y}}\n| birth_place             = [[Massillon, Ohio]]\n| death_date              = {{death date and age|2013|1|22|1928|8|03|df=y}}\n| death_place             = [[Flagstaff, Arizona]]\n| residence               = \n| citizenship             =\n| nationality             = \n| ethnicity               =\n| field                   = [[Geomorphology]]<br>[[Geology]]<br>[[Vertebrate]][[Paleontology]]\n| work_institution        = [[U.S. Geological Survey]]<br>[[Museum of Northern Arizona]]<br>Nature Expeditions International\n| alma_mater              = [[Massillon Washington High School]]<br>[[Denison University]]<br>[[University of Arizona]]\n| doctoral_advisor        = \n| doctoral_students       = \n| known_for               = [[Grand Canyon]]<br>[[Northern Arizona]]<br>[[Dilophosaurus]]<br>[[Lystrosaurus]]\n| author_abbreviation_bot = \n| author_abbreviation_zoo = \n| prizes                  = [[Fulbright Scholarship]] (1957-58)<br>[[National Science Foundation]] - Antarctic Service Medal (1977)<br>Gladys Cole Award - [[Geological Society of America]](1982)\n| religion                = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''William J. \"Bill\" Breed''' (August 3, 1928 - January 22, 2013) was an American [[geologist]], [[paleontologist]], naturalist and author in Northern [[Arizona]]. He was a renowned expert on the geology of the [[Grand Canyon]].<ref name=\"azdailysun\">[http://azdailysun.com/news/local/obituaries/william-breed-renowned-mna-geologist-dies-in-flagstaff/article_41857e06-1387-53d0-bf6f-f3c469222f65.html ''Arizona Daily Sun'', January 24, 2013, A2]</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nWilliam J. Breed was born August 3, 1928 in [[Massillon, Ohio]], son of Grace Amelia (n\u00e9e Snyder) and Earl Fremont Breed. After graduating from [[Massillon Washington High School]], he served in the U.S. Army Corps of Military Police in South Korea and Japan (1946\u201348).  He received his [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] from [[Denison University]], then his [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] and [[Master of Science|M.S.]] from [[University of Arizona]], finishing in 1960.  He married Carol S. Breed daughter of [[James Neilson (director)]] and Mrs. Ruth Swope (n\u00e9e Rogers) in 1965. The couple had one daughter, Amelia, who joined the family of four girls (Linda, Laura, Grace, Pamela) from Carol's first marriage.<ref>''Arizona Daily Sun'', Dec. 18, 1965</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\nBill Breed was a [[Fulbright Scholar]] at [[Canterbury University]] in [[Christchurch]], New Zealand to study [[geomorphology]] in 1957-58.<ref name=\"CantonRepository\">''Canton Repository'', March 12, 1957</ref>\n\nBill Breed was a prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of [[Edwin D. McKee]].  Breed was Curator of Geology (1960\u201378), Head, Geology Department (1978\u201381) at the [[Museum of Northern Arizona]] in [[Flagstaff, Arizona]]. In 1969, Breed and [[Edwin H. Colbert]] were two of the four vertebrate paleontologists in Antarctica who helped solidify the acceptance of [[continental drift]] theory, by finding a 220-million-year-old fossil of a ''[[Lystrosaurus]]''.  In the 1970s, Breed completed numerous publications on the [[Grand Canyon]], including a geologic cross section map of the Grand Canyon, San Francisco Peaks and Verde Valley; and the book, ''Geology of the Grand Canyon''.<ref>[http://azdailysun.com/news/local/obituaries/william-breed-renowned-mna-geologist-dies-in-flagstaff/article_41857e06-1387-53d0-bf6f-f3c469222f65.html Arizona Daily Sun, January 24, 2013, A2;]</ref>\n\nA species of ''[[Dilophosaurus]], (D. breedorum)'', discovered by Sam Welles in Arizona in 1964 was named after William J. Breed and his wife at the time Carol S. Breed.<ref>Welles, S. P. (1984). \"Dilophosaurus wetherilli (Dinosauria, Theropoda), osteology and comparisons\". Palaeontogr. Abt. A 185: 85\u2013180.</ref> This name came out in a private publication distributed by Pickering,<ref>Olshevsky, George (1999-12-05). \"Dinosaur Genera List corrections #126\". Dinosaur Mailing List Archives. Cleveland Museum of Natural History. Retrieved 2008-06-25.</ref> but has not been accepted in other reviews of the genus.<ref>Gay, Robert (2001). \"New specimens of Dilophosaurus wetherilli (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the early Jurassic Kayenta Formation of northern Arizona\". Western Association of Vertebrate Paleontologists annual meeting volume Mesa, Arizona 1: 1.</ref><ref>Tykoski, R. S. & Rowe, T. (2004). \"Ceratosauria\". In: Weishampel, D.B., Dodson, P., & Osmolska, H. (Eds.) ''The Dinosauria'' (2nd edition). Berkeley: University of California Press. Pp. 47\u201370 {{ISBN|0-520-24209-2}}</ref><ref>[[Dilophosaurus]]</ref>\n\nAfter leaving the [[Museum of Northern Arizona]] in 1981, Breed became a naturalist guide for Nature Expeditions International and Betchart Expeditions leading trips to Alaska, New Zealand, [[Galapagos]], [[Namibia]], and Australia.  He became Curator Emeritus of the Museum of Northern Arizona in 2004.  In January 2013, shortly before his death, Breed was named a Distinguished Fellow of the Museum of Northern Arizona.<ref name=\"azdailysun\" />\n\nBreed was an active environmentalist with [[Ted Danson]] <ref>[http://newsweek.com/2011/03/20/my-favorite-mistake.html \"My Favorite Mistake\"] ''Newsweek''</ref> and many others.\n\n== Awards ==\n\n[[Fellow]] of the [[Geological Society of America]], the A.A.A.S, the Arizona Academy of Science, and the [[Museum of Northern Arizona]].<ref name=\"Museumof\">Museum of Northern Arizona Archive</ref><br>\n[[National Science Foundation]] - Antarctic Service Medal (1977)<ref name=\"Museumof\" /><br>\n[[Geological Society of America]] - Gladys Cole Award (1982)<ref name=\"Museumof\" /><br>\nDistinguished Citizen Award from [[Massillon Washington High School]] in 2005.<ref name=\"Museumof\" />\n\n== Publications ==\n\nBreed wrote or contributed to more than 80 scientific publications and popular magazines.<ref name=\"Museumof\" />\n*1964: \"Metacoceras bowmani, a new species of Nautiloid from the Toroweap Formation (Permian) of Arizona,\" ''[[Journal of Paleontology]]''; v.38, No.5, pp 877\u2013880 (with Halsey W. Miller Jr)\n*1965: \"An exotic occurrence of fresh water drum fish,\" ''[[Plateau (journal)|Plateau]]'' v. 37, No.3, p.&nbsp;5.\n*1967: \"Evolution of the Colorado River in Arizona\" 'Museum of Northern Arizona Bulletin' #44, pp 67 (with [[Edwin D. McKee]], R.F. Wilson, and Carol S. Breed.)\n*1969: \"A Pliocene river channel near Doney Crater, Arizona\" ''Journal of Arizona Academy of Sciences'', vol. 5, No.3, pp.&nbsp;177\u2013181.\n*1969: \"The Chuar Group of the Grand Canyon, Arizona.\" ''Geological Society of America Rocky Mountain Section, Abstracts with Programs,'' May 7\u201311, 1969, pp.&nbsp;23\u201324. (with [[Trevor D. Ford]])\n*1970: \"Hopi Pahos at the South Pole\" ''Plateau'' V. 42, No. 4, pp.&nbsp;125\n*1970: \"Triassic Tetrapods from Antarctica: Evidence of Continental Drift\" ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]'' V. 169, No. 3951, pp.&nbsp;1197\u20131201 (with David H Elliot, [[Edwin H. Colbert]], James Jensen and Jon S. Powell)\n*1971: \"Last Chance for Rainbow Bridge?\" ''Outdoor Arizona'', pp.&nbsp;38\u201341\n*1974: ''Geology of the Grand Canyon'', by William J. Breed and Evelyn C. Roat \n*1974: \"Red Mountain, Erosion or Explosion,\" ''Plateau'', Vol. 46, No. 3, pp.&nbsp;120\u2013122.\n*1975: ''Geologic Cross Section of the Grand Canyon - San Francisco Peaks - Verde Valley Region'' Zion Natural History Association, Springdale, Utah\n*1976: \"Our \"Unchanging\" Grand Canyon\", ''[[Arizona Highways]]'', Vol. 52, No. 5, p.&nbsp;12-15.\n*1977: \"Chitinozoans from the Late Precambrian Chuar Group of the Grand Canyon, Arizona\" ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]'', Vol. 195, No. 4279, pp.&nbsp;676\u2013679 (with Bonnie Bloeser, Wiliam J. Schopf and Robert J. Horodyski)\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links and references ==\n\n* ''Arizona Daily Sun'', January 24, 2013, A2 http://azdailysun.com/news/local/obituaries/william-breed-renowned-mna-geologist-dies-in-flagstaff/article_41857e06-1387-53d0-bf6f-f3c469222f65.html\n*''Newsweek'': [http://newsweek.com/2011/03/20/my-favorite-mistake.html My Favorite Mistake]\n\n{{Authority control|VIAF=73915523}}\n\n<!-- This will add a notice to the bottom of the page and won't blank it! The new template which says that your draft is waiting for a review will appear at the bottom; simply ignore the old (grey) drafted templates and the old (red) decline templates. A bot will update your article submission. Until then, please don't change anything in this text box.  Just press \"Save page\". -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Breed, William J.}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:Denison University alumni]]\n[[Category:American paleontologists]]\n[[Category:American geologists]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Massillon, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Writers from Tucson, Arizona]]\n[[Category:People from Flagstaff, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Fulbright Scholars]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Geological Society of America]]\n", "name_user": "Vahurzpu", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links and references:Remove incorrect VIAF", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_J._Breed"}
{"title_page": "Luke Murphy", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Luke Murphy\n| image = lukemurphy.png\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Murphy playing for [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] in 2013\n| fullname = Luke John Murphy<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.efl.com/siteassets/efl-documents/efl-professional-retain-list--free-transfers---2017-18.pdf |title=Club list of registered players: As at 19th May 2018: Leeds United |publisher=English Football League |format=PDF |page=21 |accessdate=17 June 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1989|10|21|df=y}}<ref name=\"Hugman2010-11\">{{cite book\n | editor-first = Barry J.\n | editor-last = Hugman\n | title = The PFA Footballers' Who's Who 2010\u201311\n | year = 2010\n | publisher = Mainstream Publishing\n | isbn = 978-1-84596-601-0\n | page = 301 }}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Macclesfield]], England\n| height = {{height|ft=6|in=2}}<ref name=\"Hugman2010-11\"/>\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]\n| clubnumber = 8\n| youthyears1 = {{0|0000}}\u20132008\n| youthclubs1 = [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]]\n| years1 = 2008\u20132013 \n| clubs1 = [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]]\n| caps1  = 161 \n| goals1 = 21\n| years2 = 2013\u20132018     \n| clubs2 = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| caps2  = 103 \n| goals2 = 7\n| years3 = 2017      \n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]] (loan)\n| caps3  = 19 \n| goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 2017\u20132018      \n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]] (loan)\n| caps4  = 38 \n| goals4 = 1\n| years5 = 2018\u2013         \n| clubs5 = [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]\n| caps5  = 40\n| goals5 = 2\n| club-update = 08:00, 11 March 2020 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Luke John Murphy''' (born 21 October 1989) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for {{English football updater|BoltonWa}} club [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]].\n\nHe is a product of [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]]'s academy. He was Crewe captain prior to spending five years at Leeds. Had the chance to move to Barcelona but the dream was short lived as Daniel Gater said no no you can do one silly bastards.\n\n==Career==\n===Crewe Alexandra===\nBorn in [[Macclesfield]], [[Cheshire]],<ref name=\"Hugman2010-11\"/> Murphy made his debut for [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] on 13 December 2008 in a 1\u20130 home win against [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]].<ref>[http://www.crewealex.net/page/MatchReport/0,,10414~44377,00.html \"Crewe 1\u20130 Swindon\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090413144757/http://www.crewealex.net/page/MatchReport/0%2C%2C10414~44377%2C00.html |date=13 April 2009 }} Crewe Alexandra F.C. 13 December 2008. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref> He scored his first goal for Crewe in a 4\u20131 away win against [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] on 28 December 2008.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/7787794.stm \"Hartlepool 1\u20134 Crewe\"] BBC Sport. 28 December 2008. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref> His second goal for the club came in a 3\u20132 [[FA Cup]] replay loss to [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] on 13 January 2009.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/7815354.stm \"Crewe 2\u20133 Millwall\"] BBC Sport. 13 January 2009. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref> He finished his breakthrough season with 11 appearances as Crewe were relegated from [[EFL League One|League One]]. He scored his first goal of the 2009\u201310 season in a 5\u20133 away loss to [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]]<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8267068.stm \"Accrington 5\u20133 Crewe\"] BBC Sport. 25 September 2009. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref> and scored his second and final goal of the season in a 3\u20132 away win against [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]] on 2 December.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8377497.stm \"Chesterfield 2\u20133 Crewe\"] BBC Sport. 2 December 2009. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref>\n\nMurphy scored his first goal of the 2010\u201311 season on 11 September 2010 in a 3\u20130 win against [[Bury F.C.|Bury]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8967890.stm \"Crewe 3\u20130 Bury\"] BBC Sport. 11 September 2010. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref> He scored again the following game in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8989357.stm \"Burton 1\u20131 Crewe\"] BBC Sport. 18 September 2010. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref> His third goal of the season came in a 5\u20135 draw away to eventual [[EFL League Two|League Two]] winners Chesterfield.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/9036831.stm \"Chesterfield 5\u20135 Crewe\"] BBC Sport. 2 October 2010. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref> Murphy extended his contract with Crewe in November 2010.\n\nMurphy missed the final month of the 2010\u201311 season after having a hernia operation. During the 2011\u201312 pre-season Murphy who had been playing as a right winger was moved into his favoured more central position alongside [[Ashley Westwood (footballer born 1990)|Ashley Westwood]].<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/14251133\n| title     = Crewe's Luke Murphy 'fully fit' after hernia operation\n| work = BBC Sport\n| date      = 25 July 2011 }}</ref> His 10th league goal for Crewe came in the 2011\u201312 season, during a 3\u20132 against [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]], where he scored two goals.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16372031 \"Crewe 3\u20132 Plymouth\"] BBC Sport. 7 January 2012. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref> He scored his fifth goal of the 2011\u201312 season in a 2\u20130 home win to Accrington.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17023162 \"Crewe 2\u20130 Accrington\"] BBC Sport. 21 February 2012. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref> He ended the season with eight goals and helped Crewe secure promotion after beating [[Cheltenham Town]] in the [[2012 Football League Two play-off Final|2012 League Two play-off Final]] at [[Wembley Stadium]], to win promotion back to [[EFL League One|League One]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Emlyn |last=Begley |title=Cheltenham 0\u20132 Crewe |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18135731 |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=27 May 2012 |accessdate=27 May 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAfter the departure of [[Ashley Westwood (footballer born 1990)|Ashley Westwood]] to [[Aston Villa]], Murphy was appointed as the new Crewe Alexandra Captain in August 2012.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www.crewealex.net/news/article/murph-signs-for-leeds-888474.aspx?\n| title     = Murph Signs For Leeds\n| publisher = Crewe Alexandra Official Website\n| date      = 1 July 2013 }}</ref> In September 2012, Murphy signed a new 2-year deal at Crewe.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19751860\n| title     = Luke Murphy signs new two-year deal with Crewe Alexandra\n| work = BBC Sport\n| date      = 27 September 2012 }}</ref> On 7 April 2013, Murphy scored the first goal in the [[EFL Trophy|Football League Trophy]] final against [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]], which Crewe went on to win 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/sport/football/article3733272.ece\n| title     = Luke Murphy and Max Clayton hand Alexandra Johnstone's Paint Trophy\n| publisher = The Times: Football\n| date      = 8 April 2013 }}</ref> In the final match of the 2012\u201313 season, Murphy led out a Crewe Alexandra side against Walsall in a 2\u20130 win in which Murphy scored the opening goal for Crewe. The game made history being the first English fixture a side had fielded a team entirely made out of their academy players.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22229034\n| title     = Crewe 2 \u2013 Walsall 0\n| work = BBC Sport\n| date      = 27 April 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2314004/Crewe-Alexandra-manager-Steve-Davis-field-home-grown-team-final-League-One-match-Walsall.html#ixzz2XiW1vcWN\n| title     = Crewe to make history by fielding academy XI in final match of season\n| newspaper = Daily Mail\n| date      = 24 April 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| url       = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22278754\n| title     = Crewe Alexandra: Dario Gradi's academy dream set to come true\n| work = BBC Sport\n| date      = 24 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\nMurphy who was the captain of Crewe Alexandra collected the club's Player Of The Year award for the 2012\u201313 season, a season in which he scored nine goals, gained 12 assists and captained Crewe to victory for the [[EFL Trophy|Football League Trophy]]. Murphy also finished 4th in the voting for the League One player-of-the-season for 2012\u201313.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/Crewe-Alexandra-Murphy-named-player-season/story-18702204-detail/story.html#axzz2XiacXs39\n| title     = Crewe Alexandra: Murphy named player-of-the-season\n| publisher = This Is Staffordshire\n| date      = 14 April 2013 }}</ref> Murphy was also named in the 2012\u201313 [[PFA Team of the Year]] for [[League One]].<ref name=PFA1213>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/22331030 |title=Gareth Bale wins PFA Player of Year and Young Player awards |work=BBC Sport |date=28 April 2013 |accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref> After the season Murphy proclaimed that he was ready to step up to play at a higher level.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22155733\n| title     = Luke Murphy: Crewe Alexandra captain 'ready for higher level'\n| work = BBC Sport\n| date      = 15 April 2013 }}</ref> Murphy was heavily linked with a move to Premier League side [[Aston Villa]] to join up with ex-teammate [[Ashley Westwood (footballer born 1990)|Ashley Westwood]].<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www.crewechronicle.co.uk/crewe-alex-fc/crewe-alex-fc-news/2013/06/12/96135-33459168/\n| title     = Crewe Alex: Luke Murphy staying put for now amid Aston Villa rumours\n| publisher = Crewe Chronicle\n| date      = 12 June 2013 }}</ref> On 25 June, Crewe assistant manager Neil Baker revealed he expected Murphy to leave the club for a higher level and that he would go with the club's blessing.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www.itv.com/sport/football/update/2013-06-25/crewe-expect-murphy-departure/\n| title     = Crewe expect Murphy departure\n| publisher = ITV Sport\n| date      = 25 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Leeds United===\n\n====2013\u201314 season====\nIn June 2013, Crewe accepted bids believed to be over \u00a31 million from both [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] and [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] for Murphy.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22952002\n| title     = Luke Murphy: Wolves expected to sign Crewe Alexandra captain\n| work = BBC Sport\n| date      = 25 June 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| url       = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23096926\n| title     = Luke Murphy: Blackburn offer for Crewe captain accepted\n| work = BBC Sport\n| date      = 28 June 2013 }}</ref> Despite this on 1 July, Leeds United confirmed the signing of Murphy on a three-year deal.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/20130701/sought-after-midfielder-signs-up_2247585_3225407\n| title     = SOUGHT AFTER MIDFIELDER SIGNS UP\n| publisher = Leeds United Official Site\n| date      = 1 July 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/20130701/its-all-white-for-new-recruit-luke_2247585_3225560\n| title     = IT'S ALL WHITE FOR NEW RECRUIT LUKE\n| publisher = Leeds United Official Site\n| date      = 1 July 2013 }}</ref><ref name=YP>{{cite news|last=Wobschall|first=Leon|title=Leeds coup as Murphy deal imminent|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-utd/leeds-coup-as-murphy-deal-imminent-1-5812247|accessdate=1 July 2013|newspaper=Yorkshire Post|date=1 July 2013}}</ref> Crewe manager, [[Steve Davis (footballer born 1965)|Steve Davis]] revealed the transfer fee for Murphy was above \u00a31 million.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23127898\n| title     = Leeds United: Luke Murphy signs from Crewe Alexandra\n| work = BBC Sport\n| date      = 1 July 2013 }}</ref> The signing of Murphy was the first time that Leeds had spent over \u00a31 million on a transfer fee since signing [[Richard Cresswell]] in 2005.<ref name=BBC>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Cresswell eyes Premiership spot|url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/4164186.stm|accessdate=24 August 2005|newspaper=BBC Sport|date=24 August 2005}}</ref>\n\nMurphy made his debut against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] on 3 August in the first game of the season, he scored a dramatic 94th-minute winner in the game to give Leeds a 2\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/qcvg57jswo9z16qlqx9nsp7lh/title/brighton-live!\n| title     = Leeds 2 Brighton 1\n| publisher = Leeds United Official Site\n| date      = 3 August 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2384001/Leeds-United-2-Brighton-Hove-Albion-1-match-report-Luke-Murphy-Ross-McCormack-Leonardo-Ulloa-score-goals.html\n| title     = Leeds 2 Brighton 1: Murphy's late stunner grabs the spoils at a packed Elland Road\n| newspaper = Daily Mail\n| date      = 3 August 2013 }}</ref> On 12 April 2014, Murphy scored both goals in Leeds' 2\u20130 victory against Blackpool.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/288164/report\n| title     = Leeds 2 Blackpool 0\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date      = 12 April 2014 }}</ref> On 15 April, Leeds owner [[Massimo Cellino]] revealed after the game that he advised the then Leeds manager [[Brian McDermott (footballer)|Brian McDermott]] to play Murphy in a more attacking midfield role.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://football-italia.net/47902/cellino-what-i-told-mcdermott\n| title     = Cellino: 'What I told McDermott'\n| publisher = Football Italia\n| date      = 15 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\n====2014\u201315 season====\nOn 1 August 2014, Murphy was assigned the Leeds number seven shirt for the 2014\u201315 season.<ref name=\"SQUAD NUMBERS RELEASED\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/1wncxa2kw0zr11fmlyjr0m3t53/title/squad-numbers-released|title=SQUAD NUMBERS RELEASED|publisher=Leeds United|date=1 August 2014 |first=|last=|accessdate=1 August 2014}}</ref> On 27 August 2014, Murphy was sent off in the first half against [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] to condemn Leeds to a shock 2\u20131 League Cup defeat against the [[EFL League One|League One]] opposition.<ref name=\"SQUAD NUMBERS RELEASED\"/> Head coach, [[Dave Hockaday]] was sacked the following day.<ref name=\"CLUB STATEMENT: DAVID HOCKADAY\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/czqaoeenck6d1qxe2tf34eerc/title/club-statement-david-hockaday|title=CLUB STATEMENT: DAVID HOCKADAY|publisher=Leeds United|date=27 August 2014 |first=|last=|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter a long spell out of favour under new head coach [[Neil Redfearn]] Murphy returned to Leeds' starting lineup in the [[FA Cup]] 1\u20130 defeat against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] on 4 January 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/329650/report|title=Sunderland 1 Leeds 0| date=4 January 2015|accessdate=4 January 2015|publisher=Sky Sports}}</ref> He started the following league game, a 1\u20131 draw against [[Bolton Wanderers]] on 10 January.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bolton Wanderers 1-1 Leeds United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30663381|website=www.bbc.co.uk/|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=10 January 2015|date=10 January 2015}}</ref> He scored in consecutive games for Leeds, firstly helping to earn a point by equalising in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] on 17 January.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leeds United v Birmingham City: Redfearn hails character of Murphy|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds-united-v-birmingham-city-redfearn-hails-character-of-murphy-1-7056875|newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post|accessdate=17 January 2015|date=17 January 2015}}</ref> He then scored the winner, with a long range strike, in a 1\u20130 win against [[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] on 20 January.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leeds 1-0 Bournemouth: Luke Murphy's first-half stunner halts Cherries progress at the top of the Championship|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2918951/Leeds-1-0-Bournemouth-Luke-Murphy-s-half-stunner-halts-Cherries-progress-Championship.html|newspaper=Daily Mail|accessdate=20 January 2015|date=20 January 2015}}</ref> As a result of his rise in form over this period Murphy was subsequently nominated for the January 2015 Championship Player of the Month award.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/iyhcgkoiprvk1b2rhr5kbtlv8/title/murphy-nominated-for-january-award?|title=MURPHY NOMINATED FOR JANUARY AWARD|date=5 February 2016}}</ref> Murphy followed this up with a long range strike in a 2\u20130 victory against Reading on 10 February.<ref>{{cite news\n| url        = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2948295/Reading-0-2-Leeds-United-Luke-Murphy-Sam-Byram-strike-seal-valuable-three-points-Neil-Redfearn-s-side.html\n| title      = Reading 0 Leeds 2\n| work  = BBC Sport\n| date       = 10 February 2015\n| accessdate = 10 February 2015\n}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 May 2015, Murphy was one of five players nominated for the Fans Player Of The Year Award at Leeds United's official end of 2014\u201315 season awards ceremony, but lost out to eventual winner [[Alex Mowatt]]. Murphy also lost out to goal of the season for his goal against [[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] to teammate [[Rodolph Austin]]'s volley against Watford.<ref>{{cite news|title= MOWATT SCOOPS AWARDS NIGHT DOUBLE |date=2 May 2015|accessdate=|url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/slzwndu1a9wb1kdweft4sskxz/title/mowatt-scoops-awards-night-double|publisher=Leeds United|author=}}</ref>\n\n====2015\u201316 season====\nOn 9 July 2015, it was announced that Murphy would miss all of pre-season and the beginning of the season after picking up a knee injury which required surgery during pre season training.<ref>{{cite news|title= Blow For Whites As Murphy Undergoes Surgery |date=9 July 2015|accessdate=|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds-united-blow-for-whites-as-luke-murphy-undergoes-surgery-1-7350646|author=Yorkshire Evening Post}}</ref>\n\nDespite being out injured, on 14 July 2015, Murphy signed a new four-year contract at the club keeping him at Leeds until the summer of 2019. The contract saw Murphy actually sign on reduced terms as a considerable sign of his commitment to stay with the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=MURPHY SIGNS LONG-TERM DEAL |date=14 July 2015|accessdate=|url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/yqkdaztuqv0j16na9tiox9vna/title/murphy-signs-long-term-deal|author=Leeds United Official Site}}</ref> On 31 July 2015, Murphy was given the number 8 shirt for the upcoming 2015\u201316 season.<ref>{{cite news|publisher= Leeds United Official site | date= 31 July 2015 | accessdate= 31 July 2015 | title= 2015/16 SQUAD NUMBERS ANNOUNCED | url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/13qz1j2snco7s1ip1xc6j5mk2b/title/201516-squad-numbers-announced}}</ref> After missing all of the pre season and the beginning of the Championship season, on 12 August 2015, Murphy returned for Leeds as a substitute in the League Cup against [[Doncaster Rovers]], Murphy scored a penalty in a penalty shootout with Leeds losing 4\u20132 on penalties after a 1\u20131 draw.<ref>{{cite news|publisher= Leeds United Official site | date= 12 August 2015  | accessdate= 12 August 2015 | title= DONCASTER: UNITED EXIT CUP ON PENALTIES | url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/tq9ka0mhwvog1wx1szbqrvwzk/title/doncaster-united-exit-cup-on-penalties}}</ref> On 2 April 2016, Murphy scored his first goal of the season and Leeds' only goal in the 2\u20131 loss to [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper= Yorkshire Evening Post | date= 6 April 2016 | accessdate= 6 April 2016 | title= Leeds United: Leeds boss Evans defends 'humble and down' Bellusci| url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/leeds-rhinos/leeds-united-leeds-boss-evans-defends-humble-and-down-bellusci-1-7840929}}</ref>\n\n====2016\u201317 season====\n[[File:Luke Murphy.jpg|thumb|right|Murphy playing for Leeds United in 2016]]\nHe made his first appearance for Leeds on 23 August 2016, starting in Leeds League Cup fixture against [[Luton Town]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/15gtq6yt2p00z193z1zfdakcla/title/matchday-luton-town-live!|title=MATCHDAY: LUTON- LIVE! |publisher=Leeds United |date=23 August 2016 |accessdate=23 August 2016 }}</ref>\n\nBy 24 September, Murphy had fallen so far out of favour that he, along with [[Toumani Diagouraga]] and [[Ross Turnbull]], was no longer listed in the Leeds United match programme as a member of the squad,<ref>{{cite news|date=3 October 2016|accessdate=10 December 2016|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-ominous-signs-for-murphy-diagouraga-and-turnbull-after-leeds-leave-trio-out-of-saturday-s-squad-list-1-8160261|title=Leeds United: Ominous signs for Murphy, Diagouraga and Turnbull after Leeds leave trio out of Saturday's squad list|author=Phil Hay|newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post}}</ref> and all three were training with the under-23 team.<ref>{{cite news|date=6 December 2016|accessdate=10 December 2016|author=Phil Hay|newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post|title=Leeds United: Head coach Monk looks like he's managing|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-head-coach-monk-looks-like-he-s-managing-1-8275250}}</ref>\n\n===Burton Albion loan===\nOn 6 January 2017, Murphy left Leeds for fellow [[EFL Championship|Championship]] side [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]], on loan until the end of the 2016\u201317 season.<ref>{{cite news|work=BBC Sport|date=6 January 2017|accessdate=6 January 2017|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38530846|title=Luke Murphy: Leeds United midfielder joins Burton Albion on loan}}</ref><ref>{{citenews|url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/21481/luke-murphy-midfielder-departs-on-loan|date=6 January 2016|accessdate=6 January 2016|title=LUKE MURPHY: MIDFIELDER DEPARTS ON LOAN|publisher=Leeds United FC}}</ref><ref>{{citenews|date=6 January 2016|accessdate=6 January 2016|publisher=Burton Albion FC|url=http://www.burtonalbionfc.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/brewers-make-third-january-signing-3504473.aspx|title=BREWERS MAKE THIRD JANUARY SIGNING|author=Ash Willis}}</ref> On 28 January 2017, Murphy scored his first goal for Burton against Queens Park Rangers.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38700813|title=QPR 1-2 Burton|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=28 January 2017|accessdate=29 January 2017}}</ref> He impressed during his time at Burton, and formed a vital partnership in midfield alongside midfielder [[Jackson Irvine]] and helped the club to avoid relegation after finishing 20th.<ref>{{cite web |title=Irvine named Burton Albion player of the season |url=http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/article/2017/05/04/irvine-named-burton-albion-player-season |website=theworldgame.sbs.com.au |accessdate=24 September 2019 |date=4 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 July 2017, he re-joined Burton on loan for the entirety of the 2017\u201318 season.<ref>{{citeweb|date=3 July 2017|accessdate=3 July 2017|url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/22009/murphy-rejoins-burton|publisher=Leeds United|title=MURPHY REJOINS BURTON}}</ref> Playing in a deeper central midfield position for most of the 2017/18 season, he scored his first goal of the season on 15 April 2018, in a 3\u20131 victory against [[Derby County]].<ref>{{citeweb|date=15 April 2018|accessdate=15 April 2018|url=https://www.burtonmail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/luke-murphy-burton-albion-not-1459480|publisher=Burton Mail|title=Luke Murphy on why Burton Albion did not want Derby County to 'stick the knife in'}}</ref>\n\n====Return to Leeds====\nWith speculation that he was not in [[Marcelo Bielsa]]'s plans, on 26 July 2018, Murphy was not given a shirt number for Leeds for the upcoming [[2018\u201319 Leeds United F.C. season|2018\u201319 season]] for Leeds.<ref>{{cite news |title=2018/19 SQUAD NUMBERS ANNOUNCED |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/23576/2018-19-squad-numbers-announced |newspaper=Leeds United |date=26 July 2018 |accessdate=26 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Bolton Wanderers===\n\nHe was released from his Leeds contract, a year early, on 1 August 2018. The following day he signed for [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] on a two-year contract.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolton Wanderers sign Luke Murphy|url=https://www.bwfc.co.uk/news/2018/august/bolton-wanderers-sign-luke-murphy/ |newspaper=Bolton Wanderers F.C.|date=2 August 2018 |accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref> He made his debut for Bolton on 4 August 2018 when starting in Wanderers' 2\u20131 victory over [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] at [[The Hawthorns]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44989043|title=West Bromwich Albion 1 Bolton Wanderers 2|date=4 August 2018|accessdate=4 August 2018|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> His first goal for Bolton was on 22 October 2019, as he scored the opening goal in Bolton's first win of the 2019/2020 season, a 2\u20130 win against [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]].<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50051040</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 10 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"|[[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]]\n|[[2008\u201309 Crewe Alexandra F.C. season|2008\u201309]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|50308|2008|accessdate=13 November 2016}}</ref>\n|[[EFL League One|League One]]\n|9||1||2||1||0||0||0||0||11||2\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 Crewe Alexandra F.C. season|2009\u201310]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|50308|2009|accessdate=13 November 2016}}</ref>\n|[[EFL League Two|League Two]]\n|32||3||1||0||1||0||0||0||34||3\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 Crewe Alexandra F.C. season|2010\u201311]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|50308|2010|accessdate=13 November 2016}}</ref>\n|League Two\n|39||3||1||0||2||0||2{{Efn|name=FLT|Appearance(s) in the [[EFL Trophy]].}}||0||44||3\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Crewe Alexandra F.C. season|2011\u201312]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|50308|2011|accessdate=13 November 2016}}</ref>\n|League Two\n|42||8||1||0||1||0||5{{Efn|Three appearances in the [[EFL Trophy|Football League Trophy]] and two in the [[EFL League Two play-offs|League Two play-offs]]}}||0||49||8\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 Crewe Alexandra F.C. season|2012\u201313]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|50308|2012|accessdate=13 November 2016}}</ref>\n|League One\n|39||6||2||1||2||0||5{{Efn|name=FLT}}||2||48||9\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Crewe Alexandra total\n!1