}}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Crewe Alexandra'''\n*[[EFL League Two play-offs|Football League Two play-offs]]: [[2012 Football League play-offs#League Two|2011\u201312]]\n*[[EFL Trophy|Football League Trophy]]: [[2012\u201313 Football League Trophy|2012\u201313]]\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[PFA Team of the Year]]: [[PFA Team of the Year (2010s)#League One 4|2012\u201313 League One]]<ref name=PFA1213/>\n*[[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] Player of the Season: [[2012\u201313 Crewe Alexandra F.C. season|2012\u201313]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{2012\u201313 Football League One PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{Bolton Wanderers F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Murphy, Luke}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Macclesfield]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Crewe Alexandra F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leeds United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Burton Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bolton Wanderers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Luke Murphy\n| image = lukemurphy.png\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Murphy playing for [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] in 2013\n| fullname = Luke John Murphy<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.efl.com/siteassets/efl-documents/efl-professional-retain-list--free-transfers---2017-18.pdf |title=Club list of registered players: As at 19th May 2018: Leeds United |publisher=English Football League |format=PDF |page=21 |accessdate=17 June 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1989|10|21|df=y}}<ref name=\"Hugman2010-11\">{{cite book\n | editor-first = Barry J.\n | editor-last = Hugman\n | title = The PFA Footballers' Who's Who 2010\u201311\n | year = 2010\n | publisher = Mainstream Publishing\n | isbn = 978-1-84596-601-0\n | page = 301 }}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Macclesfield]], England\n| height = {{height|ft=6|in=2}}<ref name=\"Hugman2010-11\"/>\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]\n| clubnumber = 8\n| youthyears1 = {{0|0000}}\u20132008\n| youthclubs1 = [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]]\n| years1 = 2008\u20132013 \n| clubs1 = [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]]\n| caps1  = 161 \n| goals1 = 21\n| years2 = 2013\u20132018     \n| clubs2 = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| caps2  = 103 \n| goals2 = 7\n| years3 = 2017      \n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]] (loan)\n| caps3  = 19 \n| goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 2017\u20132018      \n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]] (loan)\n| caps4  = 38 \n| goals4 = 1\n| years5 = 2018\u2013         \n| clubs5 = [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]\n| caps5  = 40\n| goals5 = 2\n| club-update = 08:00, 11 March 2020 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Luke John Murphy''' (born 21 October 1989) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for {{English football updater|BoltonWa}} club [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]].\n\nHe is a product of [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]]'s academy. He was Crewe captain prior to spending five years at Leeds.\n\n==Career==\n===Crewe Alexandra===\nBorn in [[Macclesfield]], [[Cheshire]],<ref name=\"Hugman2010-11\"/> Murphy made his debut for [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] on 13 December 2008 in a 1\u20130 home win against [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]].<ref>[http://www.crewealex.net/page/MatchReport/0,,10414~44377,00.html \"Crewe 1\u20130 Swindon\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090413144757/http://www.crewealex.net/page/MatchReport/0%2C%2C10414~44377%2C00.html |date=13 April 2009 }} Crewe Alexandra F.C. 13 December 2008. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref> He scored his first goal for Crewe in a 4\u20131 away win against [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] on 28 December 2008.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/7787794.stm \"Hartlepool 1\u20134 Crewe\"] BBC Sport. 28 December 2008. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref> His second goal for the club came in a 3\u20132 [[FA Cup]] replay loss to [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] on 13 January 2009.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/7815354.stm \"Crewe 2\u20133 Millwall\"] BBC Sport. 13 January 2009. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref> He finished his breakthrough season with 11 appearances as Crewe were relegated from [[EFL League One|League One]]. He scored his first goal of the 2009\u201310 season in a 5\u20133 away loss to [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]]<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8267068.stm \"Accrington 5\u20133 Crewe\"] BBC Sport. 25 September 2009. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref> and scored his second and final goal of the season in a 3\u20132 away win against [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]] on 2 December.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8377497.stm \"Chesterfield 2\u20133 Crewe\"] BBC Sport. 2 December 2009. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref>\n\nMurphy scored his first goal of the 2010\u201311 season on 11 September 2010 in a 3\u20130 win against [[Bury F.C.|Bury]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8967890.stm \"Crewe 3\u20130 Bury\"] BBC Sport. 11 September 2010. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref> He scored again the following game in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8989357.stm \"Burton 1\u20131 Crewe\"] BBC Sport. 18 September 2010. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref> His third goal of the season came in a 5\u20135 draw away to eventual [[EFL League Two|League Two]] winners Chesterfield.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/9036831.stm \"Chesterfield 5\u20135 Crewe\"] BBC Sport. 2 October 2010. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref> Murphy extended his contract with Crewe in November 2010.\n\nMurphy missed the final month of the 2010\u201311 season after having a hernia operation. During the 2011\u201312 pre-season Murphy who had been playing as a right winger was moved into his favoured more central position alongside [[Ashley Westwood (footballer born 1990)|Ashley Westwood]].<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/14251133\n| title     = Crewe's Luke Murphy 'fully fit' after hernia operation\n| work = BBC Sport\n| date      = 25 July 2011 }}</ref> His 10th league goal for Crewe came in the 2011\u201312 season, during a 3\u20132 against [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]], where he scored two goals.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16372031 \"Crewe 3\u20132 Plymouth\"] BBC Sport. 7 January 2012. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref> He scored his fifth goal of the 2011\u201312 season in a 2\u20130 home win to Accrington.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17023162 \"Crewe 2\u20130 Accrington\"] BBC Sport. 21 February 2012. Retrieved 23 March 2012.</ref> He ended the season with eight goals and helped Crewe secure promotion after beating [[Cheltenham Town]] in the [[2012 Football League Two play-off Final|2012 League Two play-off Final]] at [[Wembley Stadium]], to win promotion back to [[EFL League One|League One]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Emlyn |last=Begley |title=Cheltenham 0\u20132 Crewe |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18135731 |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=27 May 2012 |accessdate=27 May 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAfter the departure of [[Ashley Westwood (footballer born 1990)|Ashley Westwood]] to [[Aston Villa]], Murphy was appointed as the new Crewe Alexandra Captain in August 2012.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www.crewealex.net/news/article/murph-signs-for-leeds-888474.aspx?\n| title     = Murph Signs For Leeds\n| publisher = Crewe Alexandra Official Website\n| date      = 1 July 2013 }}</ref> In September 2012, Murphy signed a new 2-year deal at Crewe.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19751860\n| title     = Luke Murphy signs new two-year deal with Crewe Alexandra\n| work = BBC Sport\n| date      = 27 September 2012 }}</ref> On 7 April 2013, Murphy scored the first goal in the [[EFL Trophy|Football League Trophy]] final against [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]], which Crewe went on to win 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/sport/football/article3733272.ece\n| title     = Luke Murphy and Max Clayton hand Alexandra Johnstone's Paint Trophy\n| publisher = The Times: Football\n| date      = 8 April 2013 }}</ref> In the final match of the 2012\u201313 season, Murphy led out a Crewe Alexandra side against Walsall in a 2\u20130 win in which Murphy scored the opening goal for Crewe. The game made history being the first English fixture a side had fielded a team entirely made out of their academy players.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22229034\n| title     = Crewe 2 \u2013 Walsall 0\n| work = BBC Sport\n| date      = 27 April 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2314004/Crewe-Alexandra-manager-Steve-Davis-field-home-grown-team-final-League-One-match-Walsall.html#ixzz2XiW1vcWN\n| title     = Crewe to make history by fielding academy XI in final match of season\n| newspaper = Daily Mail\n| date      = 24 April 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| url       = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22278754\n| title     = Crewe Alexandra: Dario Gradi's academy dream set to come true\n| work = BBC Sport\n| date      = 24 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\nMurphy who was the captain of Crewe Alexandra collected the club's Player Of The Year award for the 2012\u201313 season, a season in which he scored nine goals, gained 12 assists and captained Crewe to victory for the [[EFL Trophy|Football League Trophy]]. Murphy also finished 4th in the voting for the League One player-of-the-season for 2012\u201313.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/Crewe-Alexandra-Murphy-named-player-season/story-18702204-detail/story.html#axzz2XiacXs39\n| title     = Crewe Alexandra: Murphy named player-of-the-season\n| publisher = This Is Staffordshire\n| date      = 14 April 2013 }}</ref> Murphy was also named in the 2012\u201313 [[PFA Team of the Year]] for [[League One]].<ref name=PFA1213>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/22331030 |title=Gareth Bale wins PFA Player of Year and Young Player awards |work=BBC Sport |date=28 April 2013 |accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref> After the season Murphy proclaimed that he was ready to step up to play at a higher level.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22155733\n| title     = Luke Murphy: Crewe Alexandra captain 'ready for higher level'\n| work = BBC Sport\n| date      = 15 April 2013 }}</ref> Murphy was heavily linked with a move to Premier League side [[Aston Villa]] to join up with ex-teammate [[Ashley Westwood (footballer born 1990)|Ashley Westwood]].<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www.crewechronicle.co.uk/crewe-alex-fc/crewe-alex-fc-news/2013/06/12/96135-33459168/\n| title     = Crewe Alex: Luke Murphy staying put for now amid Aston Villa rumours\n| publisher = Crewe Chronicle\n| date      = 12 June 2013 }}</ref> On 25 June, Crewe assistant manager Neil Baker revealed he expected Murphy to leave the club for a higher level and that he would go with the club's blessing.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www.itv.com/sport/football/update/2013-06-25/crewe-expect-murphy-departure/\n| title     = Crewe expect Murphy departure\n| publisher = ITV Sport\n| date      = 25 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Leeds United===\n\n====2013\u201314 season====\nIn June 2013, Crewe accepted bids believed to be over \u00a31 million from both [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] and [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] for Murphy.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22952002\n| title     = Luke Murphy: Wolves expected to sign Crewe Alexandra captain\n| work = BBC Sport\n| date      = 25 June 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| url       = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23096926\n| title     = Luke Murphy: Blackburn offer for Crewe captain accepted\n| work = BBC Sport\n| date      = 28 June 2013 }}</ref> Despite this on 1 July, Leeds United confirmed the signing of Murphy on a three-year deal.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/20130701/sought-after-midfielder-signs-up_2247585_3225407\n| title     = SOUGHT AFTER MIDFIELDER SIGNS UP\n| publisher = Leeds United Official Site\n| date      = 1 July 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/20130701/its-all-white-for-new-recruit-luke_2247585_3225560\n| title     = IT'S ALL WHITE FOR NEW RECRUIT LUKE\n| publisher = Leeds United Official Site\n| date      = 1 July 2013 }}</ref><ref name=YP>{{cite news|last=Wobschall|first=Leon|title=Leeds coup as Murphy deal imminent|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-utd/leeds-coup-as-murphy-deal-imminent-1-5812247|accessdate=1 July 2013|newspaper=Yorkshire Post|date=1 July 2013}}</ref> Crewe manager, [[Steve Davis (footballer born 1965)|Steve Davis]] revealed the transfer fee for Murphy was above \u00a31 million.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23127898\n| title     = Leeds United: Luke Murphy signs from Crewe Alexandra\n| work = BBC Sport\n| date      = 1 July 2013 }}</ref> The signing of Murphy was the first time that Leeds had spent over \u00a31 million on a transfer fee since signing [[Richard Cresswell]] in 2005.<ref name=BBC>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Cresswell eyes Premiership spot|url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/4164186.stm|accessdate=24 August 2005|newspaper=BBC Sport|date=24 August 2005}}</ref>\n\nMurphy made his debut against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] on 3 August in the first game of the season, he scored a dramatic 94th-minute winner in the game to give Leeds a 2\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/qcvg57jswo9z16qlqx9nsp7lh/title/brighton-live!\n| title     = Leeds 2 Brighton 1\n| publisher = Leeds United Official Site\n| date      = 3 August 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2384001/Leeds-United-2-Brighton-Hove-Albion-1-match-report-Luke-Murphy-Ross-McCormack-Leonardo-Ulloa-score-goals.html\n| title     = Leeds 2 Brighton 1: Murphy's late stunner grabs the spoils at a packed Elland Road\n| newspaper = Daily Mail\n| date      = 3 August 2013 }}</ref> On 12 April 2014, Murphy scored both goals in Leeds' 2\u20130 victory against Blackpool.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/288164/report\n| title     = Leeds 2 Blackpool 0\n| publisher = Sky Sports\n| date      = 12 April 2014 }}</ref> On 15 April, Leeds owner [[Massimo Cellino]] revealed after the game that he advised the then Leeds manager [[Brian McDermott (footballer)|Brian McDermott]] to play Murphy in a more attacking midfield role.<ref>{{cite news\n| url       = http://football-italia.net/47902/cellino-what-i-told-mcdermott\n| title     = Cellino: 'What I told McDermott'\n| publisher = Football Italia\n| date      = 15 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\n====2014\u201315 season====\nOn 1 August 2014, Murphy was assigned the Leeds number seven shirt for the 2014\u201315 season.<ref name=\"SQUAD NUMBERS RELEASED\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/1wncxa2kw0zr11fmlyjr0m3t53/title/squad-numbers-released|title=SQUAD NUMBERS RELEASED|publisher=Leeds United|date=1 August 2014 |first=|last=|accessdate=1 August 2014}}</ref> On 27 August 2014, Murphy was sent off in the first half against [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] to condemn Leeds to a shock 2\u20131 League Cup defeat against the [[EFL League One|League One]] opposition.<ref name=\"SQUAD NUMBERS RELEASED\"/> Head coach, [[Dave Hockaday]] was sacked the following day.<ref name=\"CLUB STATEMENT: DAVID HOCKADAY\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/czqaoeenck6d1qxe2tf34eerc/title/club-statement-david-hockaday|title=CLUB STATEMENT: DAVID HOCKADAY|publisher=Leeds United|date=27 August 2014 |first=|last=|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter a long spell out of favour under new head coach [[Neil Redfearn]] Murphy returned to Leeds' starting lineup in the [[FA Cup]] 1\u20130 defeat against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] on 4 January 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/329650/report|title=Sunderland 1 Leeds 0| date=4 January 2015|accessdate=4 January 2015|publisher=Sky Sports}}</ref> He started the following league game, a 1\u20131 draw against [[Bolton Wanderers]] on 10 January.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bolton Wanderers 1-1 Leeds United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30663381|website=www.bbc.co.uk/|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=10 January 2015|date=10 January 2015}}</ref> He scored in consecutive games for Leeds, firstly helping to earn a point by equalising in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] on 17 January.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leeds United v Birmingham City: Redfearn hails character of Murphy|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds-united-v-birmingham-city-redfearn-hails-character-of-murphy-1-7056875|newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post|accessdate=17 January 2015|date=17 January 2015}}</ref> He then scored the winner, with a long range strike, in a 1\u20130 win against [[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] on 20 January.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leeds 1-0 Bournemouth: Luke Murphy's first-half stunner halts Cherries progress at the top of the Championship|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2918951/Leeds-1-0-Bournemouth-Luke-Murphy-s-half-stunner-halts-Cherries-progress-Championship.html|newspaper=Daily Mail|accessdate=20 January 2015|date=20 January 2015}}</ref> As a result of his rise in form over this period Murphy was subsequently nominated for the January 2015 Championship Player of the Month award.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/iyhcgkoiprvk1b2rhr5kbtlv8/title/murphy-nominated-for-january-award?|title=MURPHY NOMINATED FOR JANUARY AWARD|date=5 February 2016}}</ref> Murphy followed this up with a long range strike in a 2\u20130 victory against Reading on 10 February.<ref>{{cite news\n| url        = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2948295/Reading-0-2-Leeds-United-Luke-Murphy-Sam-Byram-strike-seal-valuable-three-points-Neil-Redfearn-s-side.html\n| title      = Reading 0 Leeds 2\n| work  = BBC Sport\n| date       = 10 February 2015\n| accessdate = 10 February 2015\n}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 May 2015, Murphy was one of five players nominated for the Fans Player Of The Year Award at Leeds United's official end of 2014\u201315 season awards ceremony, but lost out to eventual winner [[Alex Mowatt]]. Murphy also lost out to goal of the season for his goal against [[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] to teammate [[Rodolph Austin]]'s volley against Watford.<ref>{{cite news|title= MOWATT SCOOPS AWARDS NIGHT DOUBLE |date=2 May 2015|accessdate=|url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/slzwndu1a9wb1kdweft4sskxz/title/mowatt-scoops-awards-night-double|publisher=Leeds United|author=}}</ref>\n\n====2015\u201316 season====\nOn 9 July 2015, it was announced that Murphy would miss all of pre-season and the beginning of the season after picking up a knee injury which required surgery during pre season training.<ref>{{cite news|title= Blow For Whites As Murphy Undergoes Surgery |date=9 July 2015|accessdate=|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds-united-blow-for-whites-as-luke-murphy-undergoes-surgery-1-7350646|author=Yorkshire Evening Post}}</ref>\n\nDespite being out injured, on 14 July 2015, Murphy signed a new four-year contract at the club keeping him at Leeds until the summer of 2019. The contract saw Murphy actually sign on reduced terms as a considerable sign of his commitment to stay with the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=MURPHY SIGNS LONG-TERM DEAL |date=14 July 2015|accessdate=|url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/yqkdaztuqv0j16na9tiox9vna/title/murphy-signs-long-term-deal|author=Leeds United Official Site}}</ref> On 31 July 2015, Murphy was given the number 8 shirt for the upcoming 2015\u201316 season.<ref>{{cite news|publisher= Leeds United Official site | date= 31 July 2015 | accessdate= 31 July 2015 | title= 2015/16 SQUAD NUMBERS ANNOUNCED | url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/13qz1j2snco7s1ip1xc6j5mk2b/title/201516-squad-numbers-announced}}</ref> After missing all of the pre season and the beginning of the Championship season, on 12 August 2015, Murphy returned for Leeds as a substitute in the League Cup against [[Doncaster Rovers]], Murphy scored a penalty in a penalty shootout with Leeds losing 4\u20132 on penalties after a 1\u20131 draw.<ref>{{cite news|publisher= Leeds United Official site | date= 12 August 2015  | accessdate= 12 August 2015 | title= DONCASTER: UNITED EXIT CUP ON PENALTIES | url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/tq9ka0mhwvog1wx1szbqrvwzk/title/doncaster-united-exit-cup-on-penalties}}</ref> On 2 April 2016, Murphy scored his first goal of the season and Leeds' only goal in the 2\u20131 loss to [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper= Yorkshire Evening Post | date= 6 April 2016 | accessdate= 6 April 2016 | title= Leeds United: Leeds boss Evans defends 'humble and down' Bellusci| url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/leeds-rhinos/leeds-united-leeds-boss-evans-defends-humble-and-down-bellusci-1-7840929}}</ref>\n\n====2016\u201317 season====\n[[File:Luke Murphy.jpg|thumb|right|Murphy playing for Leeds United in 2016]]\nHe made his first appearance for Leeds on 23 August 2016, starting in Leeds League Cup fixture against [[Luton Town]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/15gtq6yt2p00z193z1zfdakcla/title/matchday-luton-town-live!|title=MATCHDAY: LUTON- LIVE! |publisher=Leeds United |date=23 August 2016 |accessdate=23 August 2016 }}</ref>\n\nBy 24 September, Murphy had fallen so far out of favour that he, along with [[Toumani Diagouraga]] and [[Ross Turnbull]], was no longer listed in the Leeds United match programme as a member of the squad,<ref>{{cite news|date=3 October 2016|accessdate=10 December 2016|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-ominous-signs-for-murphy-diagouraga-and-turnbull-after-leeds-leave-trio-out-of-saturday-s-squad-list-1-8160261|title=Leeds United: Ominous signs for Murphy, Diagouraga and Turnbull after Leeds leave trio out of Saturday's squad list|author=Phil Hay|newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post}}</ref> and all three were training with the under-23 team.<ref>{{cite news|date=6 December 2016|accessdate=10 December 2016|author=Phil Hay|newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post|title=Leeds United: Head coach Monk looks like he's managing|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-head-coach-monk-looks-like-he-s-managing-1-8275250}}</ref>\n\n===Burton Albion loan===\nOn 6 January 2017, Murphy left Leeds for fellow [[EFL Championship|Championship]] side [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]], on loan until the end of the 2016\u201317 season.<ref>{{cite news|work=BBC Sport|date=6 January 2017|accessdate=6 January 2017|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38530846|title=Luke Murphy: Leeds United midfielder joins Burton Albion on loan}}</ref><ref>{{citenews|url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/21481/luke-murphy-midfielder-departs-on-loan|date=6 January 2016|accessdate=6 January 2016|title=LUKE MURPHY: MIDFIELDER DEPARTS ON LOAN|publisher=Leeds United FC}}</ref><ref>{{citenews|date=6 January 2016|accessdate=6 January 2016|publisher=Burton Albion FC|url=http://www.burtonalbionfc.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/brewers-make-third-january-signing-3504473.aspx|title=BREWERS MAKE THIRD JANUARY SIGNING|author=Ash Willis}}</ref> On 28 January 2017, Murphy scored his first goal for Burton against Queens Park Rangers.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38700813|title=QPR 1-2 Burton|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=28 January 2017|accessdate=29 January 2017}}</ref> He impressed during his time at Burton, and formed a vital partnership in midfield alongside midfielder [[Jackson Irvine]] and helped the club to avoid relegation after finishing 20th.<ref>{{cite web |title=Irvine named Burton Albion player of the season |url=http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/article/2017/05/04/irvine-named-burton-albion-player-season |website=theworldgame.sbs.com.au |accessdate=24 September 2019 |date=4 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 July 2017, he re-joined Burton on loan for the entirety of the 2017\u201318 season.<ref>{{citeweb|date=3 July 2017|accessdate=3 July 2017|url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/22009/murphy-rejoins-burton|publisher=Leeds United|title=MURPHY REJOINS BURTON}}</ref> Playing in a deeper central midfield position for most of the 2017/18 season, he scored his first goal of the season on 15 April 2018, in a 3\u20131 victory against [[Derby County]].<ref>{{citeweb|date=15 April 2018|accessdate=15 April 2018|url=https://www.burtonmail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/luke-murphy-burton-albion-not-1459480|publisher=Burton Mail|title=Luke Murphy on why Burton Albion did not want Derby County to 'stick the knife in'}}</ref>\n\n====Return to Leeds====\nWith speculation that he was not in [[Marcelo Bielsa]]'s plans, on 26 July 2018, Murphy was not given a shirt number for Leeds for the upcoming [[2018\u201319 Leeds United F.C. season|2018\u201319 season]] for Leeds.<ref>{{cite news |title=2018/19 SQUAD NUMBERS ANNOUNCED |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/23576/2018-19-squad-numbers-announced |newspaper=Leeds United |date=26 July 2018 |accessdate=26 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Bolton Wanderers===\n\nHe was released from his Leeds contract, a year early, on 1 August 2018. The following day he signed for [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] on a two-year contract.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolton Wanderers sign Luke Murphy|url=https://www.bwfc.co.uk/news/2018/august/bolton-wanderers-sign-luke-murphy/ |newspaper=Bolton Wanderers F.C.|date=2 August 2018 |accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref> He made his debut for Bolton on 4 August 2018 when starting in Wanderers' 2\u20131 victory over [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] at [[The Hawthorns]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44989043|title=West Bromwich Albion 1 Bolton Wanderers 2|date=4 August 2018|accessdate=4 August 2018|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> His first goal for Bolton was on 22 October 2019, as he scored the opening goal in Bolton's first win of the 2019/2020 season, a 2\u20130 win against [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]].<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50051040</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 10 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"|[[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]]\n|[[2008\u201309 Crewe Alexandra F.C. season|2008\u201309]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|50308|2008|accessdate=13 November 2016}}</ref>\n|[[EFL League One|League One]]\n|9||1||2||1||0||0||0||0||11||2\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 Crewe Alexandra