16\"/>\n|Championship\n|19||1||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||20||1\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Burton Albion F.C. season|2017\u201318]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|50308|2017|accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|36||1||1||0||2||0||0||0||39||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Burton Albion total\n!55!!2!!2!!0!!2!!0!!0!!0!!59!!2\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]\n|[[2018\u201319 Bolton Wanderers F.C. season|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|50308|2018|accessdate=24 July 2019}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|11||0||2||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||13||0\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Bolton Wanderers F.C. season|2019\u201320]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|50308|2019|accessdate=5 August 2019}}</ref>\n|League One\n|29||2||1||0||1||0||1{{Efn|name=FLT}}||0||32||2\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Bolton Wanderers total\n!40!!2!!3!!0!!1!!0!!1!!0!!45!!2\n|-\n!colspan=3|Career total\n!359!!32!!15!!2!!14!!0!!13!!2!!401!!36\n|}\n;Notes\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Crewe Alexandra'''\n*[[EFL League Two play-offs|Football League Two play-offs]]: [[2012 Football League play-offs#League Two|2011\u201312]]\n*[[EFL Trophy|Football League Trophy]]: [[2012\u201313 Football League Trophy|2012\u201313]]\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[PFA Team of the Year]]: [[PFA Team of the Year (2010s)#League One 4|2012\u201313 League One]]<ref name=PFA1213/>\n*[[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] Player of the Season: [[2012\u201313 Crewe Alexandra F.C. season|2012\u201313]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{2012\u201313 Football League One PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{Bolton Wanderers F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Murphy, Luke}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Macclesfield]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Crewe Alexandra F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leeds United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Burton Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bolton Wanderers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n", "name_user": "92.31.145.206", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luke_Murphy"}
{"title_page": "Askam and Ireleth", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =                England     \n|coordinates = {{coord|54.189|-3.204|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name=           Askam and Ireleth \n|civil_parish=            Askam and Ireleth\n|population =             3632\n|population_ref=          (2001)<ref name=\"Population\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/536/642/1752/1754/3837712243.xls|title=Cumbria population figures|accessdate=9 March 2007|year=2001|format=XLS|work=2001 census|publisher=Cumbria County Council|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927010203/http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/536/642/1752/1754/3837712243.xls|archivedate=27 September 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|shire_district=          [[Borough of Barrow-in-Furness|Barrow-in-Furness]]\n|region=                  North West England\n|shire_county=            [[Cumbria]]\n|constituency_westminster=[[Barrow and Furness (UK Parliament constituency)|Barrow and Furness]]\n|post_town=               ASKAM-IN-FURNESS\n|postcode_district=       LA16\n|postcode_area=           LA \n|dial_code=               01229\n|os_grid_reference=       SD214777\n|static_image_name=       Askamandirelethlogo.jpg\n|static_image_alt=        Logo of the carish council on a rubbish bin.\n|static_image_caption=    The parish council logo. The roundel includes the initials of the villages on a symbolic representation of the beach, sea and fells.\n}}\n'''Askam and Ireleth''' is a [[civil parish]] close to [[Barrow-in-Furness]] in the county of Cumbria, in [[North West England]]. [[Historic counties of England|Historically]] part of [[Lancashire]], it originally consisted of two separate coastal villages with different origins and histories which, in recent times, have merged to become one continuous settlement. The population of the civil parish taken at the 2011 Census was 3,632.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11120167&c=Askam&d=16&e=62&g=6411250&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1453734226319&enc=1|title=Civil Parish population 2011|accessdate=25 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIreleth has its origins as a [[mediaeval]] farming village clustered on the hillside overlooking the flat sands of the [[Duddon Estuary]].<ref name=\"A Short History\">{{cite web|accessdate=9 March 2007|publisher=Mark Maclean|url=http://users.hunterlink.net.au/~mbemdm/Ireleth_Askam_history.pdf|title=A Short History of Ireleth and Askam-in-Furness|last=Maclean|first=Mark|year=1997|format=PDF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927025046/http://users.hunterlink.net.au/~mbemdm/Ireleth_Askam_history.pdf|archive-date=27 September 2007|url-status = dead}}</ref> Askam was established following the discovery of large quantities of iron ore near the village in the middle of the 18th century.\n\nThe pair originally fell within the boundaries of the [[Lonsdale (hundred)|Hundred of Lonsdale]] 'north of the sands' in the [[Historic counties of England|historic county]] of [[Lancashire]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10173000&c_id=10001043 |title=Lancashire AncC: Historical Boundaries |accessdate=9 March 2007 |publisher=A Vision of Britain Through Time |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001001412/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10173000&c_id=10001043 |archivedate=1 October 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy }}</ref> but following [[Local Government Act 1972|local government reforms]] in 1974 became part of the county of [[Cumbria]], along with the rest of [[Furness]].\n\nThe nearby [[River Duddon]] estuary and surrounding countryside have made the area well known for its wildlife,<ref name=estuary/> while the villages' exposed position on the eastern bank facing the [[Irish Sea]] have encouraged the establishment of [[wind power|wind energy]] generation, amid local controversy.\n\n==History==\n\n===Ireleth===\n[[Image:Old Ireleth map (1850-1873).PNG|thumb|right|A map from between 1850 and 1873, showing Ireleth]]\n\nIreleth is the smaller and older of the two villages, with its origins stretching back to the [[Viking]] occupation of Britain. It was originally clustered along a stream, named 'Hole Beck', about half a mile up the hill from the estuary below. It was also the junction of four roads passing through the area. Firstly, there was the 'Sands' road, named 'Marsh Lane' in maps of the 1850s, heading down the hill towards the shore, where it met one of the possible routes for crossing the treacherous tidal sands of the [[River Duddon|Duddon]] at low tide. Secondly, there was the lane heading north along a ridge towards [[Kirkby-in-Furness]]. Part of these two roads form today's A595 main road. There was also a road leading up the stream's valley towards the hamlet of [[Marton, Cumbria|Marton]], and finally a road east over the hills towards [[Dalton-in-Furness]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://planaccess.barrowbc.gov.uk/historicbarrow/PlanAccessGUI.html|title=Map from between 1850 and 1873, showing Ireleth|accessdate=24 March 2007|format=Flash|work=PlanAccess GUI|publisher=Barrow Borough Council|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928030744/http://planaccess.barrowbc.gov.uk/historicbarrow/PlanAccessGUI.html|archivedate=28 September 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Viking]] origins exist in two forms: remains have been found near St. Peter's parish church<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> and the name of the village itself is Viking, translated from the [[Old Norse]] as 'hill-slope of the Irish'.<ref>{{cite book|last=Mills|first=David|title=The Place Names of Lancashire|year=1976|publisher=Batsford|location=London|isbn=0-7134-3248-9|page=100}}</ref>\n\nIt is thought the village was included in the [[Domesday Book]], compiled soon after the [[Norman Conquest]], but there is debate over which of the entries for the [[Furness]] area in [[William the Conqueror]]'s census actually refers to modern day Ireleth.<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> Several sources name a settlement called ''Gerleuuorde'', part of the [[Manor of Hougun]], as the correct entry but there is no conclusive evidence to support this, not least because of the discrepancies in spelling.<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> Samuel Lewis' ''A Topological Dictionary of England'', written 1848, posits a different contender as the true Ireleth. He claimed ''Ouregrave'' referred to the village because of the existence of a mill named ''Orga-Mill'', but he conceded this was also conjecture. Lewis' full text on Ireleth is below.<ref name= Topological>{{cite book|last=Lewis|first=Samuel|authorlink=Samuel Lewis (publisher)|title=A Topographical Dictionary of England|year=1848|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/source.asp?pubid=445|edition=Seventh|series=A Topographical Dictionary of...|publisher=Samuel Lewis and Co.|location=London, England|chapter=Ireleth|chapterurl=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.asp?compid=51064#s7}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|\nIRELETH, a chapelry, in the parish of Dalton-In-Furness, union of Ulverston, hundred of Lonsdale north of the Sands, N. division of Lancashire, 3 miles (N.) from Dalton; containing 744 inhabitants. Ogra-Mill, in this township, has been conjectured to be the Ouregrave of the Domesday survey: Roanhead is the point for crossing Dudden sands by the ancient road into Cumberland. Upon the east borders of Ireleth, also called Above Town, are the iron-mines of Whitridge, Lindal Moor, Cross Gates, and Inman Gill, the richest and most productive mines in Furness, with the exception of Cross Gates, the works of which have been suspended. Many thousand tons of ore are raised annually in the township. The living is a perpetual curacy; net income, \u00a3100; patron, the Vicar of Dalton. The chapel was built in 1608, by Giles Brownrigg, and was originally intended for a school.\n}}\n\n[[Image:Irelethstpeters-improved.jpg|thumb|St. Peter's church (CoE), at the top of Ireleth]]\n\nDuring the [[Middle Ages]], the entire area was controlled by the [[Cistercian]] monks of [[Furness Abbey]]. During this time, Ireleth was little more than one of many farming communities in Furness. The iron ore developments of Askam largely bypassed Ireleth, and the village developed slowly, housing farmers and workers from local towns.<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> The religious history of the village is recorded as starting around the year 1608, when an endowment was created to fund a village school. Giles Brownrigg, named variously as a local landowner<ref name=\"school history\">{{cite web |url=http://www.irelethst-peters.cumbria.sch.uk/history.htm |title=History of St Peter's Ireleth |accessdate=9 March 2007 |publisher=Ireleth St. Peter's school |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060926082257/http://www.irelethst-peters.cumbria.sch.uk/history.htm |archivedate=26 September 2006 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> or a tailor who had left the area to make his fortune in London,<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> gave money to establish a school house and a salary for a schoolmaster. This building existed on what is today Sun Street; the only remains today are a font and a plaque, kept in the modern day school building, inscribed:<ref name=\"school history\"/>\n\n{{cquote|\n''Giles Brownrig caused this school house to be builded the 6 yeare of King James ano 1608 and gave a yearly salari to the schole maister for ever [sic]''\n}}\n\nIreleth featured in the ''[[Imperial Gazetteer of England and Wales]]''. In this, it is said-<ref name=\"Ireleth Imperial\">{{cite book|last=Wilson|first=John Marius|title=Imperial Gazetteer of England and Wales|year=1872|chapter=Ireleth|chapterurl=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/descriptions/entry_page.jsp?text_id=752290&word=NULL}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|\nIRELETH, a village and a chapelry in Dalton-in-Furness parish, Lancashire. The village stands at a st. of the Furness railway, on the E side of the Duddon sands, 2\u00be miles N of Dalton; is a small sub port to Lancaster; and maintains communication across the sands at low water. The chapelry includes also the hamlets of Lindale and Marton; but does not appear to have definite limits. Post town, Dalton-in-Furness. The living is a p. curacy in the diocese of Carlisle. Value, \u00a3100.* Patron, the Vicar of Dalton. The church stands on an eminence, overlooking the Duddon.\n}}\n\nIreleth did not have a parish church at this point, falling into the 'Above Town' area, together with the hamlets of Marton and Lindal, of the parish of [[Dalton-in-Furness]].<ref name=Topological/> Lacking a place of worship, it was decided the newly built school could also be put to use as a chapel. Fishwick's 'Lancashire & Cheshire Church Surveys, 1649\u20131655' of 1849 cites this record from a church survey taken in 1650:<ref>{{cite book|last=Fishwick|first=H.|title=Lancashire & Cheshire Church Surveys, 1649\u20131655|year=1879|chapter-format=Flash|pages=138|chapter=Parochial chapel: Dalton in Furness, Ireleth chapel|chapterurl= http://eagle.cch.kcl.ac.uk:8080/cce/locations/CreateLocationFrames.jsp?locKey=8869}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|\nThat the Chappell of Irleth is not farr distant from its parish Church [Dalton in Furness], but neare enough thereto, and was onely built for a schoole, and some for their perticuler ease would have the same made a Chappell [sic]\n}}\n\nIn 1860, Ireleth, along with the newly founded Askam, petitioned for the creation of its own parish<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> following the rapid increase in population. Construction of a parish church began, with the money to build St. Peter's coming from the new-found profits of iron ore mining, giving rise to the name the 'Iron Church'. It was dedicated for use on St. Peter's Day, 29 June 1865,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.visitcumbria.com/sl/ireleth-and-askam-st-peters-church/|title=Ireleth & Askam \u2013 St Peter's Church|accessdate=1 April 2016|date=21 January 2005|publisher=Visit Cumbria}}</ref> but approval for a new ecclesiastical parish of 'Ireleth-with-Askam' did not come until almost ten years later in 1874.<ref>{{cite book|last=Youngs|first=F.|title=Local Administrative Units: Northern England|year=1991|publisher=Royal Historical Society|location=London, England|pages=176|chapter=Cited by A Vision of Britain Through Time, on their Askam With Ireleth entry|chapterurl=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10368583&c_id=}}</ref>\n\n===Askam===\n[[File:Askam Pier - south.jpg|thumb|right|The south side of the pier]]\n\nAskam's history starts much more recently. In 1850, iron ore deposits were discovered in the area by [[Henry Schneider]]. These turned out to be the second largest iron ore deposits in the country, with over 7 million tons of ore extracted. By 1896, 547 men were employed in the pits by the village and in nearby [[Roanhead]], 347 of them underground. Several hundred others worked in local mines at Mouzell (between Ireleth and [[Dalton-in-Furness]]), Roanhead and Dalton.<ref>{{cite book|year=1896|url=http://www.projects.ex.ac.uk/mhn/1896-35.htm|last=Hedley|first=John L.|title=Lancashire's Mining Industry in 1896 \u2013 A List of Metalliferous Mines|publisher=Britain's Active Mining History Society}}</ref> Some were owned by the [[Myles Burton Kennedy|Kennedy]] Brothers Ltd. firm of [[Ulverston]] Barrow Haematite Steel Co and the Millom and Askam Iron Company. The latter built four [[blast furnace]]s in the village to smelt the iron ore being brought from mines all over the peninsula by rail.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.banklands.com/Wagon%20labels.htm|title=A gallery of West Cumbrian railway wagon destination cards|accessdate=10 March 2007|last=Baggerly|first=Phil|publisher=banklands.com, a tribute to the Workington iron and steel industry}}</ref> The village continued to grow with terraced houses and allotments erected for the flood of immigrant labour needed to work the mines.<ref name=\"Cumbria Directory- Askam\">{{cite web |accessdate=10 March 2007 |url=http://www.thecumbriadirectory.com/Town_or_Village/Askam_in_Furness/Askam_in_Furness.php |title=Askam in Furness Cumbria |publisher=The Cumbria Directory |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061120001255/http://www.thecumbriadirectory.com/Town_or_Village/Askam_in_Furness/Askam_in_Furness.php |archivedate=20 November 2006 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> They came from all parts of the [[British Isles]], with a large proportion coming from existing mining areas in [[Cornwall]] and Ireland. The Cornish in particular tended to bring their families and settle, while the Irish often moved on to wherever there was work. Others came from areas where Askam's mine owners had other concerns, such as Scotland and [[Wales]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.furnessfhs.co.uk/movement.htm|title=Migration and Movement|accessdate=10 March 2007|publisher=Furness Family History Society}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Askam and Ireleth signs.jpg|thumb|upright|An old Ireleth sign with a modern combined sign]]\n\nRemnants of the steel industry remain in Askam, as evidenced by a pier, consisting of slag from the works, that juts out into the bay toward [[Millom]].<ref name=\"Cumbria Directory- Askam\"/> Also, numerous streets are named after the industry and its owners. For example, 'Steel Street' is so named because of the steel industry; 'Sharp Street' is named after Joseph Sharp, one of the earliest people involved in Askam's steel industry; and 'Crossley Street' after William Crossley, an early investor in the Askam steel industry.<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> The large numbers of slag banks left by the steel industry around the village are now important sites for wildlife.<ref name=\"Estuary Booklet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.duddon-estuary.org.uk/pdf/DuddonEstuary_Booklet.pdf |title=The Duddon Estuary |accessdate=10 March 2007 |last=Thomson |first=Rona |format=PDF |publisher=The Duddon Estuary Partnership |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208110018/http://www.duddon-estuary.org.uk/pdf/DuddonEstuary_Booklet.pdf |archivedate=8 February 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy }}</ref> By 1918, the iron ore had run out and most of the industrial buildings were demolished in 1933.<ref name=\"Cumbria Directory- Askam\"/> Since then, Askam has grown with commuter homes, exploiting the views over the Duddon Estuary to the [[Lake District]].\n\n===Askam and Ireleth===\n\nAskam and Ireleth are both part of the Furness peninsula, where the suffix \"-in-Furness\" is sometimes added to place names, such as [[Barrow-in-Furness]] and [[Dalton-in-Furness]]. Askam, when referred to on its own, often uses this but it is rare for Ireleth to be called ''Ireleth-in-Furness''. \n\nHowever, Ireleth is often confused in archival records with 'Kirkby Ireleth', the former name for the community (two miles to the north) now known as [[Kirkby-in-Furness]]. These communities are differentiated in the ''Imperial Gazetteer of England and Wales''.<ref name=\"Ireleth Imperial\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Lewis|first=Samuel|authorlink=Samuel Lewis (publisher)|title=A Topographical Dictionary of England|year=1848 |edition=Seventh|series=A Topographical Dictionary of...|publisher=Samuel Lewis and Co.|location=London, England|chapter=Kirkby Ireleth|chapterurl=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.asp?compid=51082#s5}}</ref>\n\nWhile the strip development has effectively created one larger community in the past fifty years, residents of both villages still retain a strong sense of being either from Askam ''or'' Ireleth. Road signs read 'Askam and Ireleth' on entering the villages by road, but an older 'A595 \u2013 Ireleth' sign still stands on the former boundary between the two.\n\nIn administration terms, the civil parish of which they are both part uses the name Askam with Ireleth,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=362 |title=Parish and Town Councils |accessdate=10 March 2007 |publisher=Barrow Borough Council |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070310165732/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=362 |archivedate=10 March 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> as does the local [[Women's Institute|Women's Institute (WI)]] which had previously been called Ireleth WI.\n\n==Governance==\nAskam and Ireleth is part of the [[Barrow and Furness (UK Parliament constituency)|Barrow and Furness parliamentary constituency]], represented by [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party ]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] [[Simon Fell (politician)|Simon Fellk]]. \n\nFor [[Local Government]] purposes it is in the ''Dalton North [[Wards and electoral divisions of the United Kingdom|Ward]]'' of the [[Borough of Barrow-in-Furness|Barrow Council]] and the ''Dalton North division'' of [[Cumbria County Council]].\n\nThe villages have their own [[Parish councils in England|parish council]]; ''Askam and Ireleth Parish Council.''<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=10 March 2007|url= http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=362|title=Parish Councils|publisher=Barrow Borough Council|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070310165732/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=362|archivedate=10 March 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://askamandirelethparishcouncil.org.uk/|title= Askam and Ireleth Parish Council}}</ref>\n\n==Environment==\nThe upper slopes of the hill near Ireleth are home to dark blue slate, and it is found on the roofs of several local dwellings. [[Haematite]], the bright red iron ore, was discovered in an exceptionally large deposit, the second largest in the country, south of the current villages in the 1840s. Askam sprung up on the Ireleth marshes as a home for the miners attacking the new deposit. The other mineral found in large quantities, conveniently with a commercial use, is [[shale]]. This is fired with water to make red brick, and the brickworks, which is still operational today, was built in 1845 to exploit this.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.lindal-in-furness.co.uk/Geology/geology1.htm|title=Geology of Furness & Cumbria|accessdate=10 March 2007|publisher=Lindal and Martin Community Website}}</ref>\n\nMuch wildlife is found on the Duddon Estuary, including 20% of the national [[natterjack toad]] population, who are attracted to the shallow breeding pools. The slagbanks around Askam are also very important as nesting sites for the rare [[Sandwich tern]]s that live in the area.<ref name=estuary>{{cite web |url=http://www.duddon-estuary.org.uk/wildlife.htm |title=Duddon Estuary Wildlife |accessdate=10 March 2007 |last=Hutchinson |first=Kate |publisher=Duddon Estuary Partnership |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070406202850/http://www.duddon-estuary.org.uk/wildlife.htm |archivedate=6 April 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> The beach is designated a [[SSSI|Site of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI)]] because of the range of flora and fauna present on the sands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.natureonthemap.org.uk/map.aspx?map=sssi&feature=1018367,sssi-su,HYPERLINK|title=Nature on the Map :: Maps|accessdate=10 March 2007|format=Flash|publisher=Natural England}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Askam and Ireleth Wind Farm]] can be found {{convert|1.25|mi|km|0}}  east of the village, on the southern slopes of Hare Slack Hill. Work on the turbines started in late 1998, and the wind farm took eight months to complete.\n\nThe [[Marton, Cumbria|Marton]], Askam and Ireleth Windfarm Action Group was one of the first such organisations in the UK dedicated to fighting windfarm development.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=10 March 2007 |url=http://www.windfarm.fsnet.co.uk/ |title=Living With Wind Turbines |year=2004 |publisher=MAIWAG |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060420072739/http://www.windfarm.fsnet.co.uk/ |archivedate=20 April 2006 |url-status = live|df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Location and transport==\n[[File:Askam station, signalbox and crossing geograph-3240956-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|thumb|lright|Askam station and level crossing]]\n\nThe [[A595 road|A595]] is the main coastal route, designated a [[primary route]], connecting [[Dalton-in-Furness|Dalton]] and [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]] via the Cumbrian Coast. Its southern end is {{convert|2|mi|km|0}} south of Askam at the junction with the [[A590 road|A590]] Dalton-in-Furness bypass although formerly continued into Dalton. The area is served by the Blueworks X7 bus service on Wednesdays only.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/544/931/6586/6588/43406163930.pdf |title=Blueworks X7 Kirkby-In-Furness - Askam - Barrow |accessdate=14 November 2019 |format=PDF |publisher=Cumbria County Council}}</ref> There are plans to construct a crossing over the Duddon between Askam and [[Millom]] to reduce the long journey times between [[Furness]] and [[Copeland, Cumbria|Copeland]], due to the circuitous route of the A595 around the estuary. A scheme to build such a 'Duddon Crossing' remains at the planning stage, but is nominated as a future project in county transport planning.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=10 March 2007|date=November 2006|publisher=Cumbria County Council|format=PDF|url=http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/544/942/1503/3881911148.pdf|title=Area transport statements [page 24 of 50]|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927010019/http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/544/942/1503/3881911148.pdf|archivedate=27 September 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe railway line passes through the two villages virtually bisecting them, with a bridge and a [[level crossing]] by the station allowing people to cross the line. There is a stop called [[Askam Railway Station]]. Services run south to Barrow and some continue on to the [[West Coast Mainline]] at [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]]. To the north the line links to the [[Sellafield|Sellafield nuclear power plant]], a major local employer, and onwards to [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]].\n\nAskam is located on the {{convert|150|mi|km|0}} [[Cumbrian Coastal Walk]], which winds around the edge of the county.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.golakes.co.uk/Arnside-Cumbria-Coastal-Way/details/?dms=3&venue=5061122|title=Cumbria Coastal Way|accessdate=12 April 2016|publisher=GoLakes website, the official website of Cumbria Tourism}}</ref>\n\n{{NSEW|[[Kirkby-in-Furness]]|[[Barrow-in-Furness]]|[[Lindal-in-Furness]]|[[Duddon Estuary]]|[[Duddon Estuary]]|[[Marton, Cumbria|Marton]]|[[Duddon Estuary]]|[[Dalton-in-Furness]]}}\n\n==Sport==\nThe villages have several sporting facilities, including the Fallowfield Park rugby league ground, home of Askam Amateur [[Rugby league]] Football Club, known as the Sandrats. Formed on September 13, 1879,<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=10 March 2007 |url=http://www.sportskerlectables.com/enamelrugbybadges.htm |title=Eamel Rugby Badges (Askam ARLFC) |publisher=Sports Kerlectables |archivedate=10 February 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070210032537/http://www.sportskerlectables.com/enamelrugbybadges.htm |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> the amateur club is a member of [[British Amateur Rugby League Association]] and in 2007\u20132008 were elected to the [[National Conference League]] Division 2, but withdrew before the start of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalconferenceleague.co.uk/ |title=Division Two Club Register |accessdate=10 March 2007 |format=Flash |publisher=National Conference League |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070303021954/http://www.nationalconferenceleague.co.uk/ |archivedate=3 March 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> There is Askam United [[association football|Football]] Club who play in the [[West Lancashire Football League]] Division Two and Duddon SC, a [[cricket]] team based at the old K Shoes factory social club, now called Duddon Sports and Social Club. There is also a newly formed junior football team and due to playing on the Sports Club pitches, has taken the name of Duddon Sports Junior Football Club.<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=10 March 2007 |title=Clubs |url=http://barrowsportscouncil.org.uk/clubs.php |publisher=Barrow Sports Council |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070319052055/http://www.barrowsportscouncil.org.uk/clubs.php |archivedate=19 March 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nA 10-hole [[links (golf)|links]] golf course, belonging to the Dunnerholme Golf Club, lies to the north of Askam. The course has one particularly interesting feature, namely a green atop Dunnerholme Rock,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uk-golfguide.com/england/25548.html |title=Dunnerholme Golf Club |accessdate=10 March 2007 |publisher=UK Golf Guide |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070211214812/http://www.uk-golfguide.com/england/25548.html |archivedate=11 February 2007 |url-status = live|df=dmy }}</ref> a large uneroded [[limestone]] rock which stands out from the surrounding flat course and sands.<ref name=\"Estuary Booklet\"/> The golf club has been in existence since 1905.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geocities.com/dunnerholmegolfclub |title=Dunnerholme Golf Club |accessdate=10 March 2007 |publisher=Dunnerholme Golf Club |archivedate=6 February 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206004521/http://www.geocities.com/dunnerholmegolfclub |url-status = live|df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Public buildings==\n\n===Village halls===\nAskam and Ireleth has four village halls: Temperance Hall in Ireleth, Askam Community Centre (formerly part of Askam School) which was refurbished in 2010, Band Hall in Sandy Lane, the home of Askam & Ireleth Silver Band, the local [[brass band]], and venue for dances, and Rankin Hall in Askam.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.askamandirelethparishcouncil.org.uk/links.html|title=Useful links and contacts|work=askamandirelethparishcouncil.org.uk|publisher=Askam and Ireleth Parish Council}}</ref> Temperance Hall was built by the [[Quakers]] in 1872;<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> it was marked as a place of worship on Ordnance Survey maps of the late 19th century, and was used by the [[Bible Christians]], a [[Methodism|Methodist]] denomination. It later fell out of use as a religious centre, being marked on maps in 1913 as simply a hall. The Temperance Hall was closed before being renovated in the 1990s, and is now used as a community centre and the location of [[Parish councils in England|parish council]] alternate months with the Rankin Hall, which is also the meeting place for the local [[Women's Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Ireleth/SavesLaneBibleChristian.shtml|title=Saves Lane Bible Christian, Ireleth with Askam|accessdate=10 March 2007|last=Stringer|first=Phil|date=14 February 2007|publisher=GENUKI}}</ref>\n\n===Churchs===\nThere is St. Peter's Church overlooking the two villages atop Ireleth Hill, which is the oldest of the churches in the villages, and holds the only churchyard in the villages and adjoins the local cemetery; and the Temperance Hall that was once used as a church. There are three other places of worship within the village.\n\nIn 1907, at a cost of \u00a3350, The Christian Meeting House was built on Crossley Street in Askam, as a [[Church of Christ]] Church. This became, in 1956, [[Anthony the Great|St. Anthony]]'s [[Catholic]] Church, and is still used in that capacity today.  Sadly it is due to close by the end of 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Ireleth/ChristianMeetingHouse.shtml|title= Christian Meeting House, Askam in Furness \u2013 Church of Christ|accessdate=11 March 2007|last=Stringer|first=Phil|date=14 February 2007|publisher=GENUKI}}</ref> On Duddon Road, in Askam, there is also a [[Methodism|Methodist]] Church, called Duddon Road Church.  This is a shared building with the Church of England and is the headquarters of the local scouts, cubs, beavers, rainbows and brownies.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wakefield|first=Bill|publisher=BBC|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/cumbria/faith/features/churches_of_cumbria/gallery/159.shtml|title=Cumbria's Places of Worship|accessdate=11 March 2007}} {{Dead link|date=April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThere were once two other churches in the village, but they are no longer in use as Churches. Zion, on Beach Street, Askam, was a Primitive Methodist church that was founded in 1870. It closed in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Ireleth/Zion.shtml|title=Zion, Ireleth with Askam \u2013 Primitive Methodist|accessdate=11 March 2007|last=Stringer|first=Phil|date=14 February 2007|publisher=GENUKI}}</ref> There was also a [[United Methodist]] Church in Askam, and though the building still stands on Duke Street, it is now used as a social club. The Church was opened in 1878, on land that was donated by the Furness Iron and Steel Company. and became the Rankin Hall (see above) The Gospel hall on Duke Street closed some five years ago.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Ireleth/DukeStreetUnitedMethodistFreeChurch.shtml|title= Duke Street United Methodist Free Church, Ireleth with Askam|accessdate=11 March 2007 |last= Stringer|first= Phil|date= 14 February 2007|publisher= GENUKI}}</ref>\n\n===Schools===\nThere are two schools, Ireleth St Peter's [[Church of England]] Primary School<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irelethst-peters.cumbria.sch.uk/ |title=St Peter's School |accessdate=10 March 2007 |publisher=Ireleth St Peter's School |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070405081606/http://www.irelethst-peters.cumbria.sch.uk/ |archivedate=5 April 2007 |url-status = live|df=dmy }}</ref> and Askam Village School,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dfes.gov.uk/cgi-bin/performancetables/dfepx1_03.pl?Code=&No=909&Type=&Mode=&School=9095207|title=Askam Village School|accessdate=10 March 2007|year=2003|publisher=[[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Department for Education and Skills]]|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040726185257/http://www.dfes.gov.uk/cgi-bin/performancetables/dfepx1_03.pl?Code=&No=909&Type=&Mode=&School=9095207|archivedate=26 July 2004|df=dmy-all}}</ref> both of which are primary schools. \n\n===Other buildings===\nThere is a [[Lifeboat (rescue)|lifeboat]] station, home of the Duddon Inshore Rescue, that was established in 1970.\n\nAskam has a fountain commemorating [[Queen Victoria]]'s [[Diamond Jubilee|Jubilee]].<ref name=\"Cumbria Directory- Askam\"/> \n\nThere is a public library in Lord Street in Askam. It was originally built in 1904 as a reading room branch of Dalton-in-Furness Library.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Cumbria}}\n*[[Listed buildings in Askam and Ireleth]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Askam and Ireleth}}\n*[http://www.askamandirelethparishcouncil.org.uk/index.html Askam and Ireleth parish council]\n\n{{Barrow-in-Furness}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Askam And Ireleth}}\n[[Category:Furness]]\n[[Category:Districts of Barrow-in-Furness]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Cumbria]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =                England     \n|coordinates = {{coord|54.189|-3.204|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name=           Askam and Ireleth \n|civil_parish=            Askam and Ireleth\n|population =             3632\n|population_ref=          (2001)<ref name=\"Population\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/536/642/1752/1754/3837712243.xls|title=Cumbria population figures|accessdate=9 March 2007|year=2001|format=XLS|work=2001 census|publisher=Cumbria County Council|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927010203/http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/536/642/1752/1754/3837712243.xls|archivedate=27 September 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|shire_district=          [[Borough of Barrow-in-Furness|Barrow-in-Furness]]\n|region=                  North West England\n|shire_county=            [[Cumbria]]\n|constituency_westminster=[[Barrow and Furness (UK Parliament constituency)|Barrow and Furness]]\n|post_town=               ASKAM-IN-FURNESS\n|postcode_district=       LA16\n|postcode_area=           LA \n|dial_code=               01229\n|os_grid_reference=       SD214777\n|static_image_name=       Askamandirelethlogo.jpg\n|static_image_alt=        Logo of the carish council on a rubbish bin.\n|static_image_caption=    The parish council logo. The roundel includes the initials of the villages on a symbolic representation of the beach, sea and fells.\n}}\n'''Askam and Ireleth''' is a [[civil parish]] close to [[Barrow-in-Furness]] in the county of Cumbria, in [[North West England]]. [[Historic counties of England|Historically]] part of [[Lancashire]], it originally consisted of two separate coastal villages with different origins and histories which, in recent times, have merged to become one continuous settlement. The population of the civil parish taken at the 2011 Census was 3,632.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11120167&c=Askam&d=16&e=62&g=6411250&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1453734226319&enc=1|title=Civil Parish population 2011|accessdate=25 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIreleth has its origins as a [[mediaeval]] farming village clustered on the hillside overlooking the flat sands of the [[Duddon Estuary]].<ref name=\"A Short History\">{{cite web|accessdate=9 March 2007|publisher=Mark Maclean|url=http://users.hunterlink.net.au/~mbemdm/Ireleth_Askam_history.pdf|title=A Short History of Ireleth and Askam-in-Furness|last=Maclean|first=Mark|year=1997|format=PDF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927025046/http://users.hunterlink.net.au/~mbemdm/Ireleth_Askam_history.pdf|archive-date=27 September 2007|url-status = dead}}</ref> Askam was established following the discovery of large quantities of iron ore near the village in the middle of the 18th century.\n\nThe pair originally fell within the boundaries of the [[Lonsdale (hundred)|Hundred of Lonsdale]] 'north of the sands' in the [[Historic counties of England|historic county]] of [[Lancashire]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10173000&c_id=10001043 |title=Lancashire AncC: Historical Boundaries |accessdate=9 March 2007 |publisher=A Vision of Britain Through Time |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001001412/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10173000&c_id=10001043 |archivedate=1 October 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy }}</ref> but following [[Local Government Act 1972|local government reforms]] in 1974 became part of the county of [[Cumbria]], along with the rest of [[Furness]].\n\nThe nearby [[River Duddon]] estuary and surrounding countryside have made the area well known for its wildlife,<ref name=estuary/> while the villages' exposed position on the eastern bank facing the [[Irish Sea]] have encouraged the establishment of [[wind power|wind energy]] generation, amid local controversy.\n\n==History==\n\n===Ireleth===\n[[Image:Old Ireleth map (1850-1873).PNG|thumb|right|A map from between 1850 and 1873, showing Ireleth]]\n\nIreleth is the smaller and older of the two villages, with its origins stretching back to the [[Viking]] occupation of Britain. It was originally clustered along a stream, named 'Hole Beck', about half a mile up the hill from the estuary below. It was also the junction of four roads passing through the area. Firstly, there was the 'Sands' road, named 'Marsh Lane' in maps of the 1850s, heading down the hill towards the shore, where it met one of the possible routes for crossing the treacherous tidal sands of the [[River Duddon|Duddon]] at low tide. Secondly, there was the lane heading north along a ridge towards [[Kirkby-in-Furness]]. Part of these two roads form today's A595 main road. There was also a road leading up the stream's valley towards the hamlet of [[Marton, Cumbria|Marton]], and finally a road east over the hills towards [[Dalton-in-Furness]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://planaccess.barrowbc.gov.uk/historicbarrow/PlanAccessGUI.html|title=Map from between 1850 and 1873, showing Ireleth|accessdate=24 March 2007|format=Flash|work=PlanAccess GUI|publisher=Barrow Borough Council|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928030744/http://planaccess.barrowbc.gov.uk/historicbarrow/PlanAccessGUI.html|archivedate=28 September 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Viking]] origins exist in two forms: remains have been found near St. Peter's parish church<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> and the name of the village itself is Viking, translated from the [[Old Norse]] as 'hill-slope of the Irish'.<ref>{{cite book|last=Mills|first=David|title=The Place Names of Lancashire|year=1976|publisher=Batsford|location=London|isbn=0-7134-3248-9|page=100}}</ref>\n\nIt is thought the village was included in the [[Domesday Book]], compiled soon after the [[Norman Conquest]], but there is debate over which of the entries for the [[Furness]] area in [[William the Conqueror]]'s census actually refers to modern day Ireleth.<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> Several sources name a settlement called ''Gerleuuorde'', part of the [[Manor of Hougun]], as the correct entry but there is no conclusive evidence to support this, not least because of the discrepancies in spelling.<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> Samuel Lewis' ''A Topological Dictionary of England'', written 1848, posits a different contender as the true Ireleth. He claimed ''Ouregrave'' referred to the village because of the existence of a mill named ''Orga-Mill'', but he conceded this was also conjecture. Lewis' full text on Ireleth is below.<ref name= Topological>{{cite book|last=Lewis|first=Samuel|authorlink=Samuel Lewis (publisher)|title=A Topographical Dictionary of England|year=1848|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/source.asp?pubid=445|edition=Seventh|series=A Topographical Dictionary of...|publisher=Samuel Lewis and Co.|location=London, England|chapter=Ireleth|chapterurl=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.asp?compid=51064#s7}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|\nIRELETH, a chapelry, in the parish of Dalton-In-Furness, union of Ulverston, hundred of Lonsdale north of the Sands, N. division of Lancashire, 3 miles (N.) from Dalton; containing 744 inhabitants. Ogra-Mill, in this township, has been conjectured to be the Ouregrave of the Domesday survey: Roanhead is the point for crossing Dudden sands by the ancient road into Cumberland. Upon the east borders of Ireleth, also called Above Town, are the iron-mines of Whitridge, Lindal Moor, Cross Gates, and Inman Gill, the richest and most productive mines in Furness, with the exception of Cross Gates, the works of which have been suspended. Many thousand tons of ore are raised annually in the township. The living is a perpetual curacy; net income, \u00a3100; patron, the Vicar of Dalton. The chapel was built in 1608, by Giles Brownrigg, and was originally intended for a school.\n}}\n\n[[Image:Irelethstpeters-improved.jpg|thumb|St. Peter's church (CoE), at the top of Ireleth]]\n\nDuring the [[Middle Ages]], the entire area was controlled by the [[Cistercian]] monks of [[Furness Abbey]]. During this time, Ireleth was little more than one of many farming communities in Furness. The iron ore developments of Askam largely bypassed Ireleth, and the village developed slowly, housing farmers and workers from local towns.<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> The religious history of the village is recorded as starting around the year 1608, when an endowment was created to fund a village school. Giles Brownrigg, named variously as a local landowner<ref name=\"school history\">{{cite web |url=http://www.irelethst-peters.cumbria.sch.uk/history.htm |title=History of St Peter's Ireleth |accessdate=9 March 2007 |publisher=Ireleth St. Peter's school |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060926082257/http://www.irelethst-peters.cumbria.sch.uk/history.htm |archivedate=26 September 2006 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> or a tailor who had left the area to make his fortune in London,<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> gave money to establish a school house and a salary for a schoolmaster. This building existed on what is today Sun Street; the only remains today are a font and a plaque, kept in the modern day school building, inscribed:<ref name=\"school history\"/>\n\n{{cquote|\n''Giles Brownrig caused this school house to be builded the 6 yeare of King James ano 1608 and gave a yearly salari to the schole maister for ever [sic]''\n}}\n\nIreleth featured in the ''[[Imperial Gazetteer of England and Wales]]''. In this, it is said-<ref name=\"Ireleth Imperial\">{{cite book|last=Wilson|first=John Marius|title=Imperial Gazetteer of England and Wales|year=1872|chapter=Ireleth|chapterurl=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/descriptions/entry_page.jsp?text_id=752290&word=NULL}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|\nIRELETH, a village and a chapelry in Dalton-in-Furness parish, Lancashire. The village stands at a st. of the Furness railway, on the E side of the Duddon sands, 2\u00be miles N of Dalton; is a small sub port to Lancaster; and maintains communication across the sands at low water. The chapelry includes also the hamlets of Lindale and Marton; but does not appear to have definite limits. Post town, Dalton-in-Furness. The living is a p. curacy in the diocese of Carlisle. Value, \u00a3100.* Patron, the Vicar of Dalton. The church stands on an eminence, overlooking the Duddon.\n}}\n\nIreleth did not have a parish church at this point, falling into the 'Above Town' area, together with the hamlets of Marton and Lindal, of the parish of [[Dalton-in-Furness]].<ref name=Topological/> Lacking a place of worship, it was decided the newly built school could also be put to use as a chapel. Fishwick's 'Lancashire & Cheshire Church Surveys, 1649\u20131655' of 1849 cites this record from a church survey taken in 1650:<ref>{{cite book|last=Fishwick|first=H.|title=Lancashire & Cheshire Church Surveys, 1649\u20131655|year=1879|chapter-format=Flash|pages=138|chapter=Parochial chapel: Dalton in Furness, Ireleth chapel|chapterurl= http://eagle.cch.kcl.ac.uk:8080/cce/locations/CreateLocationFrames.jsp?locKey=8869}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|\nThat the Chappell of Irleth is not farr distant from its parish Church [Dalton in Furness], but neare enough thereto, and was onely built for a schoole, and some for their perticuler ease would have the same made a Chappell [sic]\n}}\n\nIn 1860, Ireleth, along with the newly founded Askam, petitioned for the creation of its own parish<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> following the rapid increase in population. Construction of a parish church began, with the money to build St. Peter's coming from the new-found profits of iron ore mining, giving rise to the name the 'Iron Church'. It was dedicated for use on St. Peter's Day, 29 June 1865,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.visitcumbria.com/sl/ireleth-and-askam-st-peters-church/|title=Ireleth & Askam \u2013 St Peter's Church|accessdate=1 April 2016|date=21 January 2005|publisher=Visit Cumbria}}</ref> but approval for a new ecclesiastical parish of 'Ireleth-with-Askam' did not come until almost ten years later in 1874.<ref>{{cite book|last=Youngs|first=F.|title=Local Administrative Units: Northern England|year=1991|publisher=Royal Historical Society|location=London, England|pages=176|chapter=Cited by A Vision of Britain Through Time, on their Askam With Ireleth entry|chapterurl=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10368583&c_id=}}</ref>\n\n===Askam===\n[[File:Askam Pier - south.jpg|thumb|right|The south side of the pier]]\n\nAskam's history starts much more recently. In 1850, iron ore deposits were discovered in the area by [[Henry Schneider]]. These turned out to be the second largest iron ore deposits in the country, with over 7 million tons of ore extracted. By 1896, 547 men were employed in the pits by the village and in nearby [[Roanhead]], 347 of them underground. Several hundred others worked in local mines at Mouzell (between Ireleth and [[Dalton-in-Furness]]), Roanhead and Dalton.<ref>{{cite book|year=1896|url=http://www.projects.ex.ac.uk/mhn/1896-35.htm|last=Hedley|first=John L.|title=Lancashire's Mining Industry in 1896 \u2013 A List of Metalliferous Mines|publisher=Britain's Active Mining History Society}}</ref> Some were owned by the [[Myles Burton Kennedy|Kennedy]] Brothers Ltd. firm of [[Ulverston]] Barrow Haematite Steel Co and the Millom and Askam Iron Company. The latter built four [[blast furnace]]s in the village to smelt the iron ore being brought from mines all over the peninsula by rail.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.banklands.com/Wagon%20labels.htm|title=A gallery of West Cumbrian railway wagon destination cards|accessdate=10 March 2007|last=Baggerly|first=Phil|publisher=banklands.com, a tribute to the Workington iron and steel industry}}</ref> The village continued to grow with terraced houses and allotments erected for the flood of immigrant labour needed to work the mines.<ref name=\"Cumbria Directory- Askam\">{{cite web |accessdate=10 March 2007 |url=http://www.thecumbriadirectory.com/Town_or_Village/Askam_in_Furness/Askam_in_Furness.php |title=Askam in Furness Cumbria |publisher=The Cumbria Directory |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061120001255/http://www.thecumbriadirectory.com/Town_or_Village/Askam_in_Furness/Askam_in_Furness.php |archivedate=20 November 2006 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> They came from all parts of the [[British Isles]], with a large proportion coming from existing mining areas in [[Cornwall]] and Ireland. The Cornish in particular tended to bring their families and settle, while the Irish often moved on to wherever there was work. Others came from areas where Askam's mine owners had other concerns, such as Scotland and [[Wales]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.furnessfhs.co.uk/movement.htm|title=Migration and Movement|accessdate=10 March 2007|publisher=Furness Family History Society}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Askam and Ireleth signs.jpg|thumb|upright|An old Ireleth sign with a modern combined sign]]\n\nRemnants of the steel industry remain in Askam, as evidenced by a pier, consisting of slag from the works, that juts out into the bay toward [[Millom]].<ref name=\"Cumbria Directory- Askam\"/> Also, numerous streets are named after the industry and its owners. For example, 'Steel Street' is so named because of the steel industry; 'Sharp Street' is named after Joseph Sharp, one of the earliest people involved in Askam's steel industry; and 'Crossley Street' after William Crossley, an early investor in the Askam steel industry.<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> The large numbers of slag banks left by the steel industry around the village are now important sites for wildlife.<ref name=\"Estuary Booklet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.duddon-estuary.org.uk/pdf/DuddonEstuary_Booklet.pdf |title=The Duddon Estuary |accessdate=10 March 2007 |last=Thomson |first=Rona |format=PDF |publisher=The Duddon Estuary Partnership |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208110018/http://www.duddon-estuary.org.uk/pdf/DuddonEstuary_Booklet.pdf |archivedate=8 February 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy }}</ref> By 1918, the iron ore had run out and most of the industrial buildings were demolished in 1933.<ref name=\"Cumbria Directory- Askam\"/> Since then, Askam has grown with commuter homes, exploiting the views over the Duddon Estuary to the [[Lake District]].\n\n===Askam and Ireleth===\n\nAskam and Ireleth are both part of the Furness peninsula, where the suffix \"-in-Furness\" is sometimes added to place names, such as [[Barrow-in-Furness]] and [[Dalton-in-Furness]]. Askam, when referred to on its own, often uses this but it is rare for Ireleth to be called ''Ireleth-in-Furness''. \n\nHowever, Ireleth is often confused in archival records with 'Kirkby Ireleth', the former name for the community (two miles to the north) now known as [[Kirkby-in-Furness]]. These communities are differentiated in the ''Imperial Gazetteer of England and Wales''.<ref name=\"Ireleth Imperial\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Lewis|first=Samuel|authorlink=Samuel Lewis (publisher)|title=A Topographical Dictionary of England|year=1848 |edition=Seventh|series=A Topographical Dictionary of...|publisher=Samuel Lewis and Co.|location=London, England|chapter=Kirkby Ireleth|chapterurl=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.asp?compid=51082#s5}}</ref>\n\nWhile the strip development has effectively created one larger community in the past fifty years, residents of both villages still retain a strong sense of being either from Askam ''or'' Ireleth. Road signs read 'Askam and Ireleth' on entering the villages by road, but an older 'A595 \u2013 Ireleth' sign still stands on the former boundary between the two.\n\nIn administration terms, the civil parish of which they are both part uses the name Askam with Ireleth,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=362 |title=Parish and Town Councils |accessdate=10 March 2007 |publisher=Barrow Borough Council |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070310165732/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=362 |archivedate=10 March 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> as does the local [[Women's Institute|Women's Institute (WI)]] which had previously been called Ireleth WI.\n\n==Governance==\nAskam and Ireleth is part of the [[Barrow and Furness (UK Parliament constituency)|Barrow and Furness parliamentary constituency]], represented by [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party ]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] [[Simon Fell (politician)|Simon Fellk]]. \n\nFor [[Local Government]] purposes it is in the ''Dalton North [[Wards and electoral divisions of the United Kingdom|Ward]]'' of the [[Borough of Barrow-in-Furness|Barrow Council]] and the ''Dalton North division'' of [[Cumbria County Council]].\n\nThe villages have their own [[Parish councils in England|parish council]]; ''Askam and Ireleth Parish Council.''<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=10 March 2007|url= http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=362|title=Parish Councils|publisher=Barrow Borough Council|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070310165732/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=362|archivedate=10 March 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://askamandirelethparishcouncil.org.uk/|title= Askam and Ireleth Parish Council}}</ref>\n\n==Environment==\nThe upper slopes of the hill near Ireleth are home to dark blue slate, and it is found on the roofs of several local dwellings. [[Haematite]], the bright red iron ore, was discovered in an exceptionally large deposit, the second largest in the country, south of the current villages in the 1840s. Askam sprung up on the Ireleth marshes as a home for the miners attacking the new deposit. The other mineral found in large quantities, conveniently with a commercial use, is [[shale]]. This is fired with water to make red brick, and the brickworks, which is still operational today, was built in 1845 to exploit this.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.lindal-in-furness.co.uk/Geology/geology1.htm|title=Geology of Furness & Cumbria|accessdate=10 March 2007|publisher=Lindal and Martin Community Website}}</ref>\n\nMuch wildlife is found on the Duddon Estuary, including 20% of the national [[natterjack toad]] population, who are attracted to the shallow breeding pools. The slagbanks around Askam are also very important as nesting sites for the rare [[Sandwich tern]]s that live in the area.<ref name=estuary>{{cite web |url=http://www.duddon-estuary.org.uk/wildlife.htm |title=Duddon Estuary Wildlife |accessdate=10 March 2007 |last=Hutchinson |first=Kate |publisher=Duddon Estuary Partnership |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070406202850/http://www.duddon-estuary.org.uk/wildlife.htm |archivedate=6 April 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> The beach is designated a [[SSSI|Site of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI)]] because of the range of flora and fauna present on the sands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.natureonthemap.org.uk/map.aspx?map=sssi&feature=1018367,sssi-su,HYPERLINK|title=Nature on the Map :: Maps|accessdate=10 March 2007|format=Flash|publisher=Natural England}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Askam and Ireleth Wind Farm]] can be found {{convert|1.25|mi|km|0}}  east of the village, on the southern slopes of Hare Slack Hill. Work on the turbines started in late 1998, and the wind farm took eight months to complete.\n\nThe [[Marton, Cumbria|Marton]], Askam and Ireleth Windfarm Action Group was one of the first such organisations in the UK dedicated to fighting windfarm development.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=10 March 2007 |url=http://www.windfarm.fsnet.co.uk/ |title=Living With Wind Turbines |year=2004 |publisher=MAIWAG |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060420072739/http://www.windfarm.fsnet.co.uk/ |archivedate=20 April 2006 |url-status = live|df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Location and transport==\n[[File:Askam station, signalbox and crossing geograph-3240956-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|thumb|lrightAskam station and level crossing]]\n\nThe [[A595 road|A595]] is the main coastal route, designated a [[primary route]], connecting [[Dalton-in-Furness|Dalton]] and [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]] via the Cumbrian Coast. Its southern end is {{convert|2|mi|km|0}} south of Askam at the junction with the [[A590 road|A590]] Dalton-in-Furness bypass although formerly continued into Dalton. The area is served by the Blueworks X7 bus service on Wednesdays only.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/544/931/6586/6588/43406163930.pdf |title=Blueworks X7 Kirkby-In-Furness - Askam - Barrow |accessdate=14 November 2019 |format=PDF |publisher=Cumbria County Council}}</ref> There are plans to construct a crossing over the Duddon between Askam and [[Millom]] to reduce the long journey times between [[Furness]] and [[Copeland, Cumbria|Copeland]], due to the circuitous route of the A595 around the estuary. A scheme to build such a 'Duddon Crossing' remains at the planning stage, but is nominated as a future project in county transport planning.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=10 March 2007|date=November 2006|publisher=Cumbria County Council|format=PDF|url=http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/544/942/1503/3881911148.pdf|title=Area transport statements [page 24 of 50]|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927010019/http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/544/942/1503/3881911148.pdf|archivedate=27 September 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe railway line passes through the two villages virtually bisecting them, with a bridge and a [[level crossing]] by the station allowing people to cross the line. There is a stop called [[Askam Railway Station]]. Services run south to Barrow and some continue on to the [[West Coast Mainline]] at [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]]. To the north the line links to the [[Sellafield|Sellafield nuclear power plant]], a major local employer, and onwards to [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]].\n\nAskam is located on the {{convert|150|mi|km|0}} [[Cumbrian Coastal Walk]], which winds around the edge of the county.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.golakes.co.uk/Arnside-Cumbria-Coastal-Way/details/?dms=3&venue=5061122|title=Cumbria Coastal Way|accessdate=12 April 2016|publisher=GoLakes website, the official website of Cumbria Tourism}}</ref>\n\n{{NSEW|[[Kirkby-in-Furness]]|[[Barrow-in-Furness]]|[[Lindal-in-Furness]]|[[Duddon Estuary]]|[[Duddon Estuary]]|[[Marton, Cumbria|Marton]]|[[Duddon Estuary]]|[[Dalton-in-Furness]]}}\n\n==Sport==\nThe villages have several sporting facilities, including the Fallowfield Park rugby league ground, home of Askam Amateur [[Rugby league]] Football Club, known as the Sandrats. Formed on September 13, 1879,<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=10 March 2007 |url=http://www.sportskerlectables.com/enamelrugbybadges.htm |title=Eamel Rugby Badges (Askam ARLFC) |publisher=Sports Kerlectables |archivedate=10 February 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070210032537/http://www.sportskerlectables.com/enamelrugbybadges.htm |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> the amateur club is a member of [[British Amateur Rugby League Association]] and in 2007\u20132008 were elected to the [[National Conference League]] Division 2, but withdrew before the start of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalconferenceleague.co.uk/ |title=Division Two Club Register |accessdate=10 March 2007 |format=Flash |publisher=National Conference League |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070303021954/http://www.nationalconferenceleague.co.uk/ |archivedate=3 March 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> There is Askam United [[association football|Football]] Club who play in the [[West Lancashire Football League]] Division Two and Duddon SC, a [[cricket]] team based at the old K Shoes factory social club, now called Duddon Sports and Social Club. There is also a newly formed junior football team and due to playing on the Sports Club pitches, has taken the name of Duddon Sports Junior Football Club.<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=10 March 2007 |title=Clubs |url=http://barrowsportscouncil.org.uk/clubs.php |publisher=Barrow Sports Council |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070319052055/http://www.barrowsportscouncil.org.uk/clubs.php |archivedate=19 March 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nA 10-hole [[links (golf)|links]] golf course, belonging to the Dunnerholme Golf Club, lies to the north of Askam. The course has one particularly interesting feature, namely a green atop Dunnerholme Rock,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uk-golfguide.com/england/25548.html |title=Dunnerholme Golf Club |accessdate=10 March 2007 |publisher=UK Golf Guide |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070211214812/http://www.uk-golfguide.com/england/25548.html |archivedate=11 February 2007 |url-status = live|df=dmy }}</ref> a large uneroded [[limestone]] rock which stands out from the surrounding flat course and sands.<ref name=\"Estuary Booklet\"/> The golf club has been in existence since 1905.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geocities.com/dunnerholmegolfclub |title=Dunnerholme Golf Club |accessdate=10 March 2007 |publisher=Dunnerholme Golf Club |archivedate=6 February 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206004521/http://www.geocities.com/dunnerholmegolfclub |url-status = live|df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Public buildings==\n\n===Village halls===\nAskam and Ireleth has four village halls: Temperance Hall in Ireleth, Askam Community Centre (formerly part of Askam School) which was refurbished in 2010, Band Hall in Sandy Lane, the home of Askam & Ireleth Silver Band, the local [[brass band]], and venue for dances, and Rankin Hall in Askam.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.askamandirelethparishcouncil.org.uk/links.html|title=Useful links and contacts|work=askamandirelethparishcouncil.org.uk|publisher=Askam and Ireleth Parish Council}}</ref> Temperance Hall was built by the [[Quakers]] in 1872;<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> it was marked as a place of worship on Ordnance Survey maps of the late 19th century, and was used by the [[Bible Christians]], a [[Methodism|Methodist]] denomination. It later fell out of use as a religious centre, being marked on maps in 1913 as simply a hall. The Temperance Hall was closed before being renovated in the 1990s, and is now used as a community centre and the location of [[Parish councils in England|parish council]] alternate months with the Rankin Hall, which is also the meeting place for the local [[Women's Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Ireleth/SavesLaneBibleChristian.shtml|title=Saves Lane Bible Christian, Ireleth with Askam|accessdate=10 March 2007|last=Stringer|first=Phil|date=14 February 2007|publisher=GENUKI}}</ref>\n\n===Churchs===\nThere is St. Peter's Church overlooking the two villages atop Ireleth Hill, which is the oldest of the churches in the villages, and holds the only churchyard in the villages and adjoins the local cemetery; and the Temperance Hall that was once used as a church. There are three other places of worship within the village.\n\nIn 1907, at a cost of \u00a3350, The Christian Meeting House was built on Crossley Street in Askam, as a [[Church of Christ]] Church. This became, in 1956, [[Anthony the Great|St. Anthony]]'s [[Catholic]] Church, and is still used in that capacity today.  Sadly it is due to close by the end of 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Ireleth/ChristianMeetingHouse.shtml|title= Christian Meeting House, Askam in Furness \u2013 Church of Christ|accessdate=11 March 2007|last=Stringer|first=Phil|date=14 February 2007|publisher=GENUKI}}</ref> On Duddon Road, in Askam, there is also a [[Methodism|Methodist]] Church, called Duddon Road Church.  This is a shared building with the Church of England and is the headquarters of the local scouts, cubs, beavers, rainbows and brownies.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wakefield|first=Bill|publisher=BBC|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/cumbria/faith/features/churches_of_cumbria/gallery/159.shtml|title=Cumbria's Places of Worship|accessdate=11 March 2007}} {{Dead link|date=April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThere were once two other churches in the village, but they are no longer in use as Churches. Zion, on Beach Street, Askam, was a Primitive Methodist church that was founded in 1870. It closed in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Ireleth/Zion.shtml|title=Zion, Ireleth with Askam \u2013 Primitive Methodist|accessdate=11 March 2007|last=Stringer|first=Phil|date=14 February 2007|publisher=GENUKI}}</ref> There was also a [[United Methodist]] Church in Askam, and though the building still stands on Duke Street, it is now used as a social club. The Church was opened in 1878, on land that was donated by the Furness Iron and Steel Company. and became the Rankin Hall (see above) The Gospel hall on Duke Street closed some five years ago.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Ireleth/DukeStreetUnitedMethodistFreeChurch.shtml|title= Duke Street United Methodist Free Church, Ireleth with Askam|accessdate=11 March 2007 |last= Stringer|first= Phil|date= 14 February 2007|publisher= GENUKI}}</ref>\n\n===Schools===\nThere are two schools, Ireleth St Peter's [[Church of England]] Primary School<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irelethst-peters.cumbria.sch.uk/ |title=St Peter's School |accessdate=10 March 2007 |publisher=Ireleth St Peter's School |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070405081606/http://www.irelethst-peters.cumbria.sch.uk/ |archivedate=5 April 2007 |url-status = live|df=dmy }}</ref> and Askam Village School,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dfes.gov.uk/cgi-bin/performancetables/dfepx1_03.pl?Code=&No=909&Type=&Mode=&School=9095207|title=Askam Village School|accessdate=10 March 2007|year=2003|publisher=[[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Department for Education and Skills]]|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040726185257/http://www.dfes.gov.uk/cgi-bin/performancetables/dfepx1_03.pl?Code=&No=909&Type=&Mode=&School=9095207|archivedate=26 July 2004|df=dmy-all}}</ref> both of which are primary schools. \n\n===Other buildings===\nThere is a [[Lifeboat (rescue)|lifeboat]] station, home of the Duddon Inshore Rescue, that was established in 1970.\n\nAskam has a fountain commemorating [[Queen Victoria]]'s [[Diamond Jubilee|Jubilee]].<ref name=\"Cumbria Directory- Askam\"/> \n\nThere is a public library in Lord Street in Askam. It was originally built in 1904 as a reading room branch of Dalton-in-Furness Library.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Cumbria}}\n*[[Listed buildings in Askam and Ireleth]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Askam and Ireleth}}\n*[http://www.askamandirelethparishcouncil.org.uk/index.html Askam and Ireleth parish council]\n\n{{Barrow-in-Furness}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Askam And Ireleth}}\n[[Category:Furness]]\n[[Category:Districts of Barrow-in-Furness]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Cumbria]]\n", "name_user": "Tgl59", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLocation and transport:Corrected image caption", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Askam_and_Ireleth"}
